on_date\":\"2026-07-08\",\"examination_date_display\":\"2026-07-08\",\"examination_time\":null,\"center_name\":\"university_hospital_wuerzburg\",\"patient_gender_name\":\"unknown\",\"endoscope_type\":null,\"endoscope_sn\":null,\"patient_hash_display\":\"...835c0a39\",\"examination_hash_display\":\"...6e9fe78c\",\"pseudo_patient_id\":17,\"pseudo_examination_id\":113,\"examiners_display\":[\"Katarzyna Junk\"],\"is_verified\":false,\"dob_verified\":false,\"names_verified\":false,\"text\":\"unknown unknown\",\"anonymized_text\":null,\"tags\":[],\"validation_comment\":\"\",\"external_id\":null,\"external_id_origin\":null},{\"id\":57,\"casenumber\":null,\"patient_first_name\":\"unknown\",\"patient_last_name\":\"unknown\",\"patient_dob\":\"1970-01-01T00:00:00-06:00\",\"patient_dob_display\":\"1970-01-01\",\"examination_date\":\"2026-05-12\",\"examination_date_display\":\"2026-05-12\",\"examination_time\":null,\"center_name\":\"university_hospital_wuerzburg\",\"patient_gender_name\":\"unknown\",\"endoscope_type\":null,\"endoscope_sn\":null,\"patient_hash_display\":\"...835c0a39\",\"examination_hash_display\":\"...db119c5e\",\"pseudo_patient_id\":17,\"pseudo_examination_id\":106,\"examiners_display\":[\"Katarzyna Junk\"],\"is_verified\":false,\"dob_verified\":false,\"names_verified\":false,\"text\":\"NASA-TLX Fragebogen\\nAngepasste Software-Evaluation (Raw-TLX, 5 Faktoren)\\nAnleitung: Bitte bewerten Sie die gerade ausgeführte Aufgabe an der Software. Setzen Sie für jede\\nder folgenden Skalen ein Kreuz oder markieren Sie den Kreis, der Ihr Empfinden am besten\\nwiderspiegelt. (Jede Skala hat 20 Abstufungen).\\nGeistige Anforderungen\\nWie viel geistige und wahrnehmungsbezogene Aktivität war erforderlich (z. B. Denken, Entscheiden,\\nRechnen, Erinnern, Suchen)?\\nGering Hoch\\nZeitliche Anforderungen\\nWie viel Zeitdruck empfanden Sie hinsichtlich der Häufigkeit oder dem Takt, mit dem Aufgaben oder\\nAufgabenelemente auftraten?\\nGering Hoch\\nEigene Leistung\\nWie erfolgreich waren Sie Ihrer Meinung nach bei der Erledigung der vorgegebenen Ziele?\\nGut Schlecht\\nAnstrengung\\nWie hart mussten Sie geistig arbeiten, um Ihren Grad an Leistung zu erreichen?\\nGering Hoch\\nFrustrationsniveau\\nWie unsicher, entmutigt, irritiert, gestresst und verärgert fühlten Sie sich während der Aufgabe?\\nGering Hoch\\nZusätzliche Anmerkungen\\nGibt es spezifische Aspekte der Software, die Ihre Bewertung besonders beeinflusst haben?\",\"anonymized_text\":\"NASA-TLX Fragebogen\\nAngepasste Software-Evaluation (Raw-TLX, 5 Faktoren)\\nAnleitung: Bitte bewerten Sie die gerade ausgeführte Aufgabe an der Software. Setzen Sie für jede\\nder folgenden Skalen ein Kreuz oder markieren Sie den Kreis, der Ihr Empfinden am besten\\nwiderspiegelt. (Jede Skala hat 20 Abstufungen).\\nGeistige Anforderungen\\nWie viel geistige und wahrnehmungsbezogene Aktivität war erforderlich (z. B. Denken, Entscheiden,\\nRechnen, Erinnern, Suchen)?\\nGering Hoch\\nZeitliche Anforderungen\\nWie viel Zeitdruck empfanden Sie hinsichtlich der Häufigkeit oder dem Takt, mit dem Aufgaben oder\\nAufgabenelemente auftraten?\\nGering Hoch\\nEigene Leistung\\nWie erfolgreich waren Sie Ihrer Meinung nach bei der Erledigung der vorgegebenen Ziele?\\nGut Schlecht\\nAnstrengung\\nWie hart mussten Sie geistig arbeiten, um Ihren Grad an Leistung zu erreichen?\\nGering Hoch\\nFrustrationsniveau\\nWie unsicher, entmutigt, irritiert, gestresst und verärgert fühlten Sie sich während der Aufgabe?\\nGering Hoch\\nZusätzliche Anmerkungen\\nGibt es spezifische Aspekte der Software, die Ihre Bewertung besonders beeinflusst haben?\",\"tags\":[],\"validation_comment\":\"\",\"external_id\":null,\"external_id_origin\":null},{\"id\":24,\"casenumber\":\"0016391299\",\"patient_first_name\":\"Klaus-Dieter\",\"patient_last_name\":\"Schmitt\",\"patient_dob\":\"1954-08-08T00:00:00-05:00\",\"patient_dob_display\":\"1954-08-08\",\"examination_date\":\"1900-01-01\",\"examination_date_display\":\"1900-01-01\",\"examination_time\":\"12:37:00\",\"center_name\":\"university_hospital_wuerzburg\",\"patient_gender_name\":\"male\",\"endoscope_type\":null,\"endoscope_sn\":null,\"patient_hash_display\":\"...a6001069\",\"examination_hash_display\":\"...a6001069\",\"pseudo_patient_id\":60,\"pseudo_examination_id\":102,\"examiners_display\":[\"Katarzyna Junk\",\"Abraham Löwer\"],\"is_verified\":true,\"dob_verified\":true,\"names_verified\":true,\"text\":\"Universitätsklinikum Würzburg\\nKlinikum der Bayerischen Julius-Maximilians-Universität\\nMedizinische Klinik und Poliklinik II\\nDirektor: Prof. Dr. H. Einsele\\nSchwerpunkt Gastroenterologie\\nLehrstuhlinhaber: Prof. Dr. A. Meining\\nMed. Klinik und Poliklinik II, ZIM\\nOberdürrbacher Str. 6-8, 97080 Würzburg\\nSCHWERPUNKT\\nDr. GASTROENTEROLOGIE\\nDaniel Grüninger\\nProf. Dr. A. Meining\\nMedizinische Klinik und Poliklinik II\\nSekretariat\\nOberdürrbacher Straße 6-8\\nFr.A. Weißenberger\\n97080 Würzburg Tel.0931 201-40201\\nEndoskopie\\nZIM Haus A4 Ebene -1\\nTel. 0931 201-40220\\nPatient: Schmitt ,Klaus-Dieter geb. 08.03.1954 Fallnummer: 0016391299\\nRotkäppchenweg 16, 97084 Würzburg\\n1. Unters.: PD Dr. Reiter, Florian U-datum:13.11.2024 12:37\\nAssist.:Fischer, Jennifer,\\nLembach, Isabell\\nIleokoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-EZ1500DL (SN 2302955)\\nAnamnese: Über Zuweiser Portal: In externa Koloskopie kleine Polypektomien, 2\\ngroße Polypen im Colon transversum und Colon descendens, jeweils ca. 20\\nmm in situ belassen.\\nVE:\\naHT\\nz.n. BronchialCA im re OL 2017\\nMedikation:\\nCandesartan\\nIndikation: Polypektomie\\nPrämedikation: 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. 750 mg Propofol i. v. (fraktioniert). 10 mg Buscopan i. v.\\nPulsoxymetrische- + Kreislaufüberwachung.\\nMaximale Einsicht: Terminales Ileum.\\nAnus: Inspektion der Analregion ohne pathologischen Befund. Unauffälliger Tastbefund.\\nSchleimhaut glatt und verschiebbar, keine Resistenzen, kein Blut am Handschuh.\\nColon: BBPS 3+3+3\\nV.a. Lipom im Colon ascendens. Hier erfolgt eine Knopflochbiopsie. Es finden sich drei\\nKnospen (1x Colon ascendens, 2x Colon sigmoideum). Diese werden mittels Cold Snare\\nmakroskopisch vollständig abgetragen (Paris Is, NICE II). Im Bereich des Caecums findet sich\\neine Narbe mit leicht polypös aufgeworfenem Gewebe. Diese wird mittels Cold Snare\\nebenfalls entfernt.\\nPatient: Schmitt Klaus-Dieter, geb. am 08.03.1954 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16391299 Untersuchung vom 13.11.2024\\n2002976084 12:37\\nIm Bereich des Colon transversum bzw. im Bereich des Colon sigmoideum/descendens finden\\nsich die zwei beschriebenen großen (bis 3cm) sessilen Polypen (NICE II, Paris Is). Beide\\nwerden zunächst mittels Glycerosteril-/Adrenalingemisch unterspritzt und heben sich gut ab.\\nDie Entfernung erfolgt mittels Diathermieschlinge. Beide Polypen können aufgrund ihrer Lage\\nüber jeweilige Faltenkämme und aufgrund der Größe nur in Piecemeal-Technik abgetragen\\nwerden. Die Wundränder werden thermokoaguliert und beide Stellen werden prophylaktisch\\nmittels Clips therapiert.\\nIm C. asc. findet sich eine Angieektasie.\\nHistologie: PE 1 Knsope C. asc\\nPE 2 Narbe Coecum\\nPE 3 V.a. Lipom\\nPE 4 Sigma piece meal großer Polyp + 2 x Knospe\\nPE 5 Transversum piece meal großer Polyp\\nAbschließende Begutachtung:\\n1.: Ein tubuläres Adenom der Dickdarmschleimhaut mit low-grade Dysplasien.\\nAngrenzend regelrecht gestaltete Dickdarmschleimhaut (Knospe Ascendens, laut\\nklinischen Angaben).\\n2.: Ein tubuläres Adenom der Dickdarmschleimhaut mit low-grade Dysplasien.\\nAngrenzend und beiliegend regelrecht gestaltete Dickdarmschleimhaut (Narbe\\nZökum, laut klinischen Angaben).\\n3.: Entzündungsfreie Dickdarmschleimhaut mit regelrechter Kryptenarchitektur.\\nSubmucosa ist nicht erfasst (V.a. Lipom, laut klinischen Angaben).\\n4.: Anteile eines oder mehrerer tubuläre Adenome der Dickdarmschleimhaut mit\\nlow-grade Dysplasien. Angrenzend regelrecht gestaltete Dickdarmschleimhaut\\n(Sigma Piece-meal großer Polyp + 2x Knospe, laut klinischen Angaben).\\n5.: Anteile eines oder mehrerer tubuläre Adenome der Dickdarmschleimhaut mit\\nlow-grade Dysplasien. Angrenzend regelrecht gestaltete Dickdarmschleimhaut\\n(Transversum Piece-meal großer Polyp, laut klinischen Angaben).\\nKein Anhalt für high-grade Dysplasien.\\nKein Anhalt für invasives Carcinomwachstum.\\nKomplikation: nein\\nBeurteilung Drei Polypknospen: Ektomie mittels Cold Snare\\nendgültig:\\nZwei große Polypen: Piecemeal-Abtragung mittels Diathermieschlinge\\nV.a. Lipom: Knopflochbiopsie\\nV.a. Rezidivpolyp im Bereich des Caecums (Narbe): Ektomie mit Cold Snare\\nAngieektasie C. asc.\\nEmpfehlung: 1. Heute nur Flüssigkost.\\n2. Hb-Kontrolle um 17 Uhr und morgen früh.\\n3. Koloskopische Kontrolle in 3–6 Monaten aufgrund der Piecemeal-Abtragung empfohlen.\\nDer Bericht wurde am 21.11.2024 erneut postalisch an den Patienten versendet.\\n___________________________\\nPD Dr. Reiter, Florian\\nPatient: Schmitt Klaus-Dieter, geb. am 08.03.1954 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16391299 Untersuchung vom 13.11.2024\\n2002976084 12:37\\nPatient: Schmitt Klaus-Dieter, geb. am 08.03.1954 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16391299 Untersuchung vom 13.11.2024\\n2002976084 12:37\",\"anonymized_text\":\"1. Unters.: PD Dr. Radisch, Silvester U-datum:16.10.2024 12:37\\nAssist.:Fischer, Jennifer,\\nLembach, Isabell\\nIleokoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-EZ1500DL (SN 2968696)\\nAnamnese: Über Zuweiser Portal: In externa Koloskopie kleine Polypektomien, 2\\ngroße Polypen im Colon transversum und Colon descendens, jeweils ca. 20\\nmm in situ belassen.\\nVE:\\naHT\\nz.n. BronchialCA im re OL 2017\\nMedikation:\\nCandesartan\\nIndikation: Polypektomie\\nPrämedikation: 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. 750 mg Propofol i. v. (fraktioniert). 10 mg Buscopan i. v.\\nPulsoxymetrische- + Kreislaufüberwachung.\\nMaximale Einsicht: Terminales Ileum.\\nAnus: Inspektion der Analregion ohne pathologischen Befund. Unauffälliger Tastbefund.\\nSchleimhaut glatt und verschiebbar, keine Resistenzen, kein Blut am Handschuh.\\nColon: BBPS 3+3+3\\nV.a. Lipom im Colon ascendens. Hier erfolgt eine Knopflochbiopsie. Es finden sich drei\\nKnospen (1x Colon ascendens, 2x Colon sigmoideum). Diese werden mittels Cold Snare\\nmakroskopisch vollständig abgetragen (Paris Is, NICE II). Im Bereich des Caecums findet sich\\neine Narbe mit leicht polypös aufgeworfenem Gewebe. Diese wird mittels Cold Snare\\nebenfalls entfernt.\\nPatient: Scholz Gerhardt, geb. am 16.05.1960 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 55061780 Untersuchung vom 16.10.2024\\n1977368384 12:37\\nIm Bereich des Colon transversum bzw. im Bereich des Colon sigmoideum/descendens finden\\nsich die zwei beschriebenen großen (bis 3cm) sessilen Polypen (NICE II, Paris Is). Beide\\nwerden zunächst mittels Glycerosteril-/Adrenalingemisch unterspritzt und heben sich gut ab.\\nDie Entfernung erfolgt mittels Diathermieschlinge. Beide Polypen können aufgrund ihrer Lage\\nüber jeweilige Faltenkämme und aufgrund der Größe nur in Piecemeal-Technik abgetragen\\nwerden. Die Wundränder werden thermokoaguliert und beide Stellen werden prophylaktisch\\nmittels Clips therapiert.\\nIm C. asc. findet sich eine Angieektasie.\\nHistologie: PE 1 Knsope C. asc\\nPE 2 Narbe Coecum\\nPE 3 V.a. Lipom\\nPE 4 Sigma piece meal großer Polyp + 2 x Knospe\\nPE 5 Transversum piece meal großer Polyp\\nAbschließende Begutachtung:\\n1.: Ein tubuläres Adenom der Dickdarmschleimhaut mit low-grade Dysplasien.\\nAngrenzend regelrecht gestaltete Dickdarmschleimhaut (Knospe Ascendens, laut\\nklinischen Angaben).\\n2.: Ein tubuläres Adenom der Dickdarmschleimhaut mit low-grade Dysplasien.\\nAngrenzend und beiliegend regelrecht gestaltete Dickdarmschleimhaut (Narbe\\nZökum, laut klinischen Angaben).\\n3.: Entzündungsfreie Dickdarmschleimhaut mit regelrechter Kryptenarchitektur.\\nSubmucosa ist nicht erfasst (V.a. Lipom, laut klinischen Angaben).\\n4.: Anteile eines oder mehrerer tubuläre Adenome der Dickdarmschleimhaut mit\\nlow-grade Dysplasien. Angrenzend regelrecht gestaltete Dickdarmschleimhaut\\n(Sigma Piece-meal großer Polyp + 2x Knospe, laut klinischen Angaben).\\n5.: Anteile eines oder mehrerer tubuläre Adenome der Dickdarmschleimhaut mit\\nlow-grade Dysplasien. Angrenzend regelrecht gestaltete Dickdarmschleimhaut\\n(Transversum Piece-meal großer Polyp, laut klinischen Angaben).\\nKein Anhalt für high-grade Dysplasien.\\nKein Anhalt für invasives Carcinomwachstum.\\nKomplikation: nein\\nBeurteilung Drei Polypknospen: Ektomie mittels Cold Snare\\nendgültig:\\nZwei große Polypen: Piecemeal-Abtragung mittels Diathermieschlinge\\nV.a. Lipom: Knopflochbiopsie\\nV.a. Rezidivpolyp im Bereich des Caecums (Narbe): Ektomie mit Cold Snare\\nAngieektasie C. asc.\\nEmpfehlung: 1. Heute nur Flüssigkost.\\n2. Hb-Kontrolle um 17 Uhr und morgen früh.\\n3. Koloskopische Kontrolle in 3–6 Monaten aufgrund der Piecemeal-Abtragung empfohlen.\\nDer Bericht wurde am 21.11.2024 erneut postalisch an den Patienten versendet.\\n___________________________\",\"tags\":[],\"validation_comment\":\"\",\"external_id\":null,\"external_id_origin\":null},{\"id\":23,\"casenumber\":null,\"patient_first_name\":\"Dirk\",\"patient_last_name\":\"Sabelmann\",\"patient_dob\":\"1970-01-01T00:00:00-06:00\",\"patient_dob_display\":\"1970-01-01\",\"examination_date\":\"2024-11-06\",\"examination_date_display\":\"2024-11-06\",\"examination_time\":\"14:30:00\",\"center_name\":\"university_hospital_wuerzburg\",\"patient_gender_name\":\"unknown\",\"endoscope_type\":null,\"endoscope_sn\":null,\"patient_hash_display\":\"...f0b0d670\",\"examination_hash_display\":\"...15eec88f\",\"pseudo_patient_id\":26,\"pseudo_examination_id\":68,\"examiners_display\":[\"Katarzyna Junk\",\"Abraham Löwer\"],\"is_verified\":false,\"dob_verified\":false,\"names_verified\":false,\"text\":\"Universitätsklinikum Würzburg\\nKlinikum der Bayerischen Julius-Maximilians-Universität\\nMedizinische Klinik und Poliklinik II\\nDirektor: Prof. Dr. H. Einsele\\nSchwerpunkt Gastroenterologie\\nLehrstuhlinhaber: Prof. Dr. A. Meining\\nMed. Klinik und Poliklinik II, ZIM\\nOberdürrbacher Str. 6-8, 97080 Würzburg\\nSCHWERPUNKT\\nGASTROENTEROLOGIE\\nNiklas Grüner\\nProf. Dr. A. Meining\\nMedizinische Klinik und Poliklinik II\\nSekretariat\\nOberdürrbacher Straße 6-8\\nFr.A. Weißenberger\\n97080 Würzburg Tel.0931 201-40201\\nEndoskopie\\nZIM Haus A4 Ebene -1\\nTel. 0931 201-40220\\nPatient: Sabelmann ,Dirk Christian geb. Fallnummer: 0016385077\\n28.07.1992\\nRosenweg 11, 74589 Satteldorf\\n1. Unters.: PD Dr. Reiter, Florian U-datum:06.11.2024 14:30\\nAssist.:Endres, Eva, Lembach,\\nIsabell\\nKoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-EZ1500DL (SN 2000543)\\nAnamnese: Sigmakarzinom (dMMR) auf dem Boden eines SPS, V.a. Lynch-Syndrom.\\nHemikolektomie links erfolgt.\\nZuletzt Koloskopie mit Sanerung des Reskolons bei multiplen SSA bis 2cm\\nam 20.08.24 erfolgt. Nun Fortführung der Abtragung.\\nIndikation: Fortsetzung Polypektomie.\\nPrämedikation: 1050 mg Propofol i. v. (fraktioniert). 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. Pulsoxymetrische- +\\nKreislaufüberwachung.\\nMaximale Einsicht: Terminales Ileum.\\nAnus: Inspektion der Analregion ohne pathologischen Befund. Unauffälliger Tastbefund. Schleimhaut\\nglatt und verschiebbar, keine Resistenzen, kein Blut am Handschuh.\\nColon: BBPS 3+3+3.\\nIm Ileum findet sich ein polypös inponierend erscheinendes Schleimhautareal. Hier wird mittels\\nKaltzange eine Biopsie gewonnen.\\nEs finden sich zahlreiche flache, zum Teil > 1 cm messende sessile Polypen (Paris IIa). Es\\nerfolgt eine aufwändige Abtragung der Polypen im rechten Colon bis zur rechten Flexur.\\nHier werden insgesamt 5 Polypen (alle NICE II und Paris IIa) mittels\\nAdrenalin/Submukosainjektion mit einer Größe > 1 cm aufgespritzt. Im Anschluss erfolgt eine\\nthermische Schlingenresektion. Die Polypen im Bereich des Caecums, ein Poylp im C. asc.\\nund der rechten Flexur werden in Piecemeal-Technik abgetragen. Es wird versucht, die\\nWundränder zu koagulieren. Bei drei der fünf Läsionen erfolgt eine prophylaktische\\nClipapplikation. Die Polypektomie des gesamten Colons kann aufgrund der prolongierten\\nUntersuchungszeit und des nun auftretenden Schluckaufs nicht vollständig durchgeführt\\nwerden.\\nPatient: Sabelmann Dirk Christian, geb. am 28.07.1992 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16385077 Untersuchung vom 06.11.2024\\n2003485553 14:30\\nKomplikation: nein\\nBeurteilung Multiple sessile Polypen. Heute Polypektomie des rechten Kolons, teilweise in\\nendgültig: Piecemeal-Technik.\\nEmpfehlung: - Wiedervorstellung im Januar 2025 zur Weiterführung der Polypektomie.\\n- Hierbei bitte auch Inspektion der Abtragungsstelle im Cooecum, C.asc. und an der rechten\\nFlexur, da hier eine piecemeal Abtragung stattfand.\\n- Heute nur Flüsskost.\\n- Heute Abend und morgen früh Hb-Kontrolle.\\n- Histologie folgt.\\n___________________________\\nPD Dr. Reiter, Florian\\nPatient: Sabelmann Dirk Christian, geb. am 28.07.1992 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16385077 Untersuchung vom 06.11.2024\\n2003485553 14:30\",\"anonymized_text\":\"1. Unters.: PD Dr. Carsten, Phillip U-datum:19.10.2024 14:30\\nAssist.:Endres, Eva, Lembach,\\nIsabell\\nKoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-EZ1500DL (SN 8164176)\\nAnamnese: Sigmakarzinom (dMMR) auf dem Boden eines SPS, V.a. Lynch-Syndrom.\\nHemikolektomie links erfolgt.\\nZuletzt Koloskopie mit Sanerung des Reskolons bei multiplen SSA bis 2cm\\nam 20.08.24 erfolgt. Nun Fortführung der Abtragung.\\nIndikation: Fortsetzung Polypektomie.\\nPrämedikation: 1050 mg Propofol i. v. (fraktioniert). 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. Pulsoxymetrische- +\\nKreislaufüberwachung.\\nMaximale Einsicht: Terminales Ileum.\\nAnus: Inspektion der Analregion ohne pathologischen Befund. Unauffälliger Tastbefund. Schleimhaut\\nglatt und verschiebbar, keine Resistenzen, kein Blut am Handschuh.\\nColon: BBPS 3+3+3.\\nIm Ileum findet sich ein polypös inponierend erscheinendes Schleimhautareal. Hier wird mittels\\nKaltzange eine Biopsie gewonnen.\\nEs finden sich zahlreiche flache, zum Teil > 1 cm messende sessile Polypen (Paris IIa). Es\\nerfolgt eine aufwändige Abtragung der Polypen im rechten Colon bis zur rechten Flexur.\\nHier werden insgesamt 5 Polypen (alle NICE II und Paris IIa) mittels\\nAdrenalin/Submukosainjektion mit einer Größe > 1 cm aufgespritzt. Im Anschluss erfolgt eine\\nthermische Schlingenresektion. Die Polypen im Bereich des Caecums, ein Poylp im C. asc.\\nund der rechten Flexur werden in Piecemeal-Technik abgetragen. Es wird versucht, die\\nWundränder zu koagulieren. Bei drei der fünf Läsionen erfolgt eine prophylaktische\\nClipapplikation. Die Polypektomie des gesamten Colons kann aufgrund der prolongierten\\nUntersuchungszeit und des nun auftretenden Schluckaufs nicht vollständig durchgeführt\\nwerden.\\nPatient: Cichorius Antonia Christian, geb. am 28.07.1992 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 37751589 Untersuchung vom 19.10.2024\\n7430570089 14:30\\nKomplikation: nein\\nBeurteilung Multiple sessile Polypen. Heute Polypektomie des rechten Kolons, teilweise in\\nendgültig: Piecemeal-Technik.\\nEmpfehlung: - Wiedervorstellung im Januar 2025 zur Weiterführung der Polypektomie.\\n- Hierbei bitte auch Inspektion der Abtragungsstelle im Cooecum, C.asc. und an der rechten\\nFlexur, da hier eine piecemeal Abtragung stattfand.\\n- Heute nur Flüsskost.\\n- Heute Abend und morgen früh Hb-Kontrolle.\\n- Histologie folgt.\\n___________________________\",\"tags\":[],\"validation_comment\":\"\",\"external_id\":null,\"external_id_origin\":null},{\"id\":22,\"casenumber\":\"0016391292\",\"patient_first_name\":\"Winfried\",\"patient_last_name\":\"Neisinger\",\"patient_dob\":\"1970-01-01T00:00:00-06:00\",\"patient_dob_display\":\"1970-01-01\",\"examination_date\":\"2024-11-13\",\"examination_date_display\":\"2024-11-13\",\"examination_time\":\"13:30:00\",\"center_name\":\"university_hospital_wuerzburg\",\"patient_gender_name\":\"male\",\"endoscope_type\":null,\"endoscope_sn\":null,\"patient_hash_display\":\"...b03bd2ac\",\"examination_hash_display\":\"...0151c234\",\"pseudo_patient_id\":25,\"pseudo_examination_id\":67,\"examiners_display\":[\"Katarzyna Junk\",\"Abraham Löwer\"],\"is_verified\":false,\"dob_verified\":false,\"names_verified\":false,\"text\":\"Universitätsklinikum Würzburg\\nKlinikum der Bayerischen Julius-Maximilians-Universität\\nMedizinische Klinik und Poliklinik II\\nDirektor: Prof. Dr. H. Einsele\\nSchwerpunkt Gastroenterologie\\nLehrstuhlinhaber: Prof. Dr. A. Meining\\nMed. Klinik und Poliklinik II, ZIM\\nOberdürrbacher Str. 6-8, 97080 Würzburg\\nSCHWERPUNKT\\nDr. GASTROENTEROLOGIE\\nJulia Bayer\\nProf. Dr. A. Meining\\nMedizinische Klinik II\\nSekretariat\\nOberdürrbacher Straße 6-8\\nFr.A. Weißenberger\\n97080 Würzburg Tel.0931 201-40201\\nEndoskopie\\nZIM Haus A4 Ebene -1\\nTel. 0931 201-40220\\nPatient: Neisinger ,Winfried geb. 29.07.1949 Fallnummer: 0016391292\\nZellinger Str. 36, 97274 Leinach\\n1. Unters.: PD Dr. Reiter, Florian U-datum:13.11.2024 13:30\\n2.Unters.: PD Dr. Brand, Markus Assist.:Fischer, Jennifer,\\nPD Dr. Lembach, Isabell\\nBrand,\\nMarkus\\nIleokoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-EZ1500DL (SN 2000543)\\nAnamnese: Coloskopie vom 23.04.24: (Praxis Langmann)\\nIm C. Ascendens ca. 5cm auf einer Falte gelegener flacher Polyp -> PE:\\nLGIEN\\nAllergien: keine bekannt\\nMedikation: keine Blutverdünnung\\nweitere Diagnosen:\\nZustand nach Schädelbasisfraktur (S02.1Z)\\nLWS-Syndrom (M54.16G)\\nArterielle Hypertonie (I10.90G)\\nHämorrhoiden 3. Grades (K64.2G)\\nChronische Antrumgastritis (K29.5G)\\nIndikation: endoskopische Resektion\\nPrämedikation: 450 mg Propofol i. v. (fraktioniert). 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. Pulsoxymetrische- +\\nKreislaufüberwachung.\\nMaximale Einsicht: Terminales Ileum.\\nAnus: Inspektion der Analregion ohne pathologischen Befund. Unauffälliger Tastbefund. Schleimhaut\\nglatt und verschiebbar, keine Resistenzen, kein Blut am Handschuh.\\nColon: Es zeigt sich ein breitbasiger Polyp im Colon ascendens mit einer Größe von 45 mm und\\nintakter Oberfläche (Paris 0-IIa, NICE II). Der Polyp wird nach einer Unterspritzung mit\\nGlycerosteril/Adrenalin makroskopisch vollständig in mehreren Stücken entfernt und geborgen.\\nPatient: Neisinger Winfried, geb. am 29.07.1949 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16391292 Untersuchung vom 13.11.2024\\n2002055645 13:30\\nDie Wundränder werden koaguliert. Keine Komplikationen.\\nHistologie: Begutachtung:\\nAnteile eines tubulo-villösen Dickdarmadenoms mit vorrangig low- und fokal auch\\nhigh-grade Epitheldysplasien und angrenzend und beiliegend immer wieder regulär\\ngestaltete Dickdarmschleimhaut (großer Polyp Colon ascendens, Polypektomie in\\npiece meal, laut klinischer Angabe). Kein invasives Carcinomwachstum.\\nKomplikation: nein\\nBeurteilung Großer Polyp Colon ascendens => Polypektomie in piece meal (D12.2)\\nvorläufig: Histologie: tubulo-villösen Dickdarmadenoms mit vorrangig low- und fokal auch\\nhigh-grade Epitheldysplasien\\nEmpfehlung: 1. Heute nur Flüssigkost.\\n2. Hb-Kontrolle um 17 Uhr und morgen früh.\\n3. Koloskopische Kontrolle in 2–6 Monaten aufgrund der Piecemeal-Abtragung empfohlen.\\nDer Befund wurde am 18.11.2024 erneut postalisch an die/den Patientin/en versendet.\\n___________________________ ___________________________\\nPD Dr. Reiter, Florian PD Dr. Brand, Markus\\nPatient: Neisinger Winfried, geb. am 29.07.1949 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16391292 Untersuchung vom 13.11.2024\\n2002055645 13:30\",\"anonymized_text\":\"1. Unters.: PD Dr. Wernecke, Edit U-datum:01.12.2024 13:30\\n2.Unters.: PD Dr. Junitz, Benjamin Assist.:Fischer, Jennifer,\\nPD Dr. Lembach, Isabell\\nJunitz,\\nBenjamin\\nIleokoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-EZ1500DL (SN 7890054)\\nAnamnese: Coloskopie vom 23.04.24: (Praxis Langmann)\\nIm C. Ascendens ca. 5cm auf einer Falte gelegener flacher Polyp -> PE:\\nLGIEN\\nAllergien: keine bekannt\\nMedikation: keine Blutverdünnung\\nweitere Diagnosen:\\nZustand nach Schädelbasisfraktur (S02.1Z)\\nLWS-Syndrom (M54.16G)\\nArterielle Hypertonie (I10.90G)\\nHämorrhoiden 3. Grades (K64.2G)\\nChronische Antrumgastritis (K29.5G)\\nIndikation: endoskopische Resektion\\nPrämedikation: 450 mg Propofol i. v. (fraktioniert). 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. Pulsoxymetrische- +\\nKreislaufüberwachung.\\nMaximale Einsicht: Terminales Ileum.\\nAnus: Inspektion der Analregion ohne pathologischen Befund. Unauffälliger Tastbefund. Schleimhaut\\nglatt und verschiebbar, keine Resistenzen, kein Blut am Handschuh.\\nColon: Es zeigt sich ein breitbasiger Polyp im Colon ascendens mit einer Größe von 45 mm und\\nintakter Oberfläche (Paris 0-IIa, NICE II). Der Polyp wird nach einer Unterspritzung mit\\nGlycerosteril/Adrenalin makroskopisch vollständig in mehreren Stücken entfernt und geborgen.\\nPatient: Rogge Tom, geb. am 29.07.1949 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 96736803 Untersuchung vom 01.12.2024\\n7589161430 13:30\\nDie Wundränder werden koaguliert. Keine Komplikationen.\\nHistologie: Begutachtung:\\nAnteile eines tubulo-villösen Dickdarmadenoms mit vorrangig low- und fokal auch\\nhigh-grade Epitheldysplasien und angrenzend und beiliegend immer wieder regulär\\ngestaltete Dickdarmschleimhaut (großer Polyp Colon ascendens, Polypektomie in\\npiece meal, laut klinischer Angabe). Kein invasives Carcinomwachstum.\\nKomplikation: nein\\nBeurteilung Großer Polyp Colon ascendens => Polypektomie in piece meal (D12.2)\\nvorläufig: Histologie: tubulo-villösen Dickdarmadenoms mit vorrangig low- und fokal auch\\nhigh-grade Epitheldysplasien\\nEmpfehlung: 1. Heute nur Flüssigkost.\\n2. Hb-Kontrolle um 17 Uhr und morgen früh.\\n3. Koloskopische Kontrolle in 2–6 Monaten aufgrund der Piecemeal-Abtragung empfohlen.\\nDer Befund wurde am 18.11.2024 erneut postalisch an die/den Patientin/en versendet.\\n___________________________ ___________________________\",\"tags\":[],\"validation_comment\":\"\",\"external_id\":null,\"external_id_origin\":null},{\"id\":21,\"casenumber\":\"0016458319\",\"patient_first_name\":\"Laura\",\"patient_last_name\":\"unknown\",\"patient_dob\":\"1970-01-01T00:00:00-06:00\",\"patient_dob_display\":\"1970-01-01\",\"examination_date\":\"2025-01-15\",\"examination_date_display\":\"2025-01-15\",\"examination_time\":\"13:30:00\",\"center_name\":\"university_hospital_wuerzburg\",\"patient_gender_name\":\"female\",\"endoscope_type\":null,\"endoscope_sn\":null,\"patient_hash_display\":\"...8e6683a6\",\"examination_hash_display\":\"...614bb981\",\"pseudo_patient_id\":24,\"pseudo_examination_id\":66,\"examiners_display\":[\"Katarzyna Junk\",\"Abraham Löwer\"],\"is_verified\":false,\"dob_verified\":false,\"names_verified\":false,\"text\":\"Universitätsklinikum Würzburg\\nKlinikum der Bayerischen Julius-Maximilians-Universität\\nMedizinische Klinik und Poliklinik II\\nDirektor: Prof. Dr. H. Einsele\\nSchwerpunkt Gastroenterologie\\nLehrstuhlinhaber: Prof. Dr. A. Meining\\nMed. Klinik und Poliklinik II, ZIM\\nOberdürrbacher Str. 6-8, 97080 Würzburg\\nSCHWERPUNKT\\nGASTROENTEROLOGIE\\nCarla Marija Viktorija Franziska Gorse\\nProf. Dr. A. Meining\\nMedizinische Klinik II\\nSekretariat\\nOberdürrbacher Straße 6-8\\nFr.A. Weißenberger\\n97080 Würzburg Tel.0931 201-40201\\nEndoskopie\\nZIM Haus A4 Ebene -1\\nTel. 0931 201-40220\\nPatient: Kretschmer ,Laura geb. 24.01.2000 Fallnummer: 0016458319\\nEngelbert-Kraus-Str. 23, 97222 Rimpar\\n1. Unters.: PD Dr. Reiter, Florian U-datum:15.01.2025 13:30\\nAssist.:Sultan, Anja, Purrer,\\nMandy\\nIleokoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-HQ190L (SN 2084327)\\nAnamnese: Vorbehandlung bei Dr. Seibel-Müntze\\nKoloskopie 11.10.2024: Schlingen Polypektomie von 2 Polypen im Zökum und\\nim Colon ascendens. Sigmadivertikulose. Abgeheilte Analfissur.\\nVerblieben etwa 2 cm große Polyp Kolon ascendens zur stationären\\nPolypektomie.\\nHistologie Polyp Zökum und Polyp Kolon ascendens: Sessiles serratiertes\\nLäsion des Kolons. Ektomie erfolgte im Gesunden. Kein Anhalt für\\nMalignität.\\nIndikation: Kolo mit Polypektomie eines ca. 2 cm großen Polypen im Colon ascendens.\\nPrämedikation: 370 mg Propofol i. v. (fraktioniert). 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. Pulsoxymetrische- +\\nKreislaufüberwachung.\\nMaximale Einsicht: Terminales Ileum.\\nAnus: Inspektion und Palpation unauffällig.\\nColon: BBPS 3+3+3\\nEs zeigt sich ein schmalbasiger Polyp im Colon ascendens mit einer Größe von 15 mm und\\nintakter Oberfläche (NICE I, Paris Is).\\nNach Infiltration mit Glycerosteril/Adrenalin (vollständige Abhebung des Polypen) wird der Polyp\\nkomplett en bloc entfernt und geborgen. Es treten keine Komplikationen auf. Zur Prophylaxe\\nerfolgt ein Wundverschluss mit einem Clip.\\nBiopsie: 1 x aus dem Colon ascendens (Polypektomie).\\nKomplikation: ja Bei Polypektomie: keine Komplikationen.\\nBeurteilung Einzelner Polyp im Colon ascendens (a.e. SSL). (D12.2)\\nPatient: Kretschmer Laura, geb. am 24.01.2000 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16458319 Untersuchung vom 15.01.2025\\n2002241467 13:30\\nvorläufig: Polypektomie im Kolon.\\nEmpfehlung: 1. Aufgrund der Polypenneigung in diesem jungen Alter sollte auch den erstgradigen\\nVerwandten eine Koloskopie empfohlen werden, sofern diese noch nicht erfolgt ist.\\n2. Die Histologie steht noch aus.\\n___________________________\\nPD Dr. Reiter, Florian\\nPatient: Kretschmer Laura, geb. am 24.01.2000 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16458319 Untersuchung vom 15.01.2025\\n2002241467 13:30\",\"anonymized_text\":\"1. Unters.: PD Dr. Baum, Irmtrud U-datum:02.02.2025 13:30\\nAssist.:Sultan, David, Schönland,\\nDorothe\\nIleokoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-HQ190L (SN 3411909)\\nAnamnese: Vorbehandlung bei Dr. Seibel-Müntze\\nKoloskopie 11.10.2024: Schlingen Polypektomie von 2 Polypen im Zökum und\\nim Colon ascendens. Sigmadivertikulose. Abgeheilte Analfissur.\\nVerblieben etwa 2 cm große Polyp Kolon ascendens zur stationären\\nPolypektomie.\\nHistologie Polyp Zökum und Polyp Kolon ascendens: Sessiles serratiertes\\nLäsion des Kolons. Ektomie erfolgte im Gesunden. Kein Anhalt für\\nMalignität.\\nIndikation: Kolo mit Polypektomie eines ca. 2 cm großen Polypen im Colon ascendens.\\nPrämedikation: 370 mg Propofol i. v. (fraktioniert). 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. Pulsoxymetrische- +\\nKreislaufüberwachung.\\nMaximale Einsicht: Terminales Ileum.\\nAnus: Inspektion und Palpation unauffällig.\\nColon: BBPS 3+3+3\\nEs zeigt sich ein schmalbasiger Polyp im Colon ascendens mit einer Größe von 15 mm und\\nintakter Oberfläche (NICE I, Paris Is).\\nNach Infiltration mit Glycerosteril/Adrenalin (vollständige Abhebung des Polypen) wird der Polyp\\nkomplett en bloc entfernt und geborgen. Es treten keine Komplikationen auf. Zur Prophylaxe\\nerfolgt ein Wundverschluss mit einem Clip.\\nBiopsie: 1 x aus dem Colon ascendens (Polypektomie).\\nKomplikation: ja Bei Polypektomie: keine Komplikationen.\\nBeurteilung Einzelner Polyp im Colon ascendens (a.e. SSL). (D12.2)\\nPatient: Kretschmer Eugen-Jochen, geb. am 24.01.2000 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 39121200 Untersuchung vom 02.02.2025\\n6920271851 13:30\\nvorläufig: Polypektomie im Kolon.\\nEmpfehlung: 1. Aufgrund der Polypenneigung in diesem jungen Alter sollte auch den erstgradigen\\nVerwandten eine Koloskopie empfohlen werden, sofern diese noch nicht erfolgt ist.\\n2. Die Histologie steht noch aus.\\n___________________________\",\"tags\":[],\"validation_comment\":\"\",\"external_id\":null,\"external_id_origin\":null},{\"id\":20,\"casenumber\":\"0016501095\",\"patient_first_name\":\"Claudia\",\"patient_last_name\":\"unknown\",\"patient_dob\":\"1970-01-01T00:00:00-06:00\",\"patient_dob_display\":\"1970-01-01\",\"examination_date\":\"2025-01-29\",\"examination_date_display\":\"2025-01-29\",\"examination_time\":\"14:00:00\",\"center_name\":\"university_hospital_wuerzburg\",\"patient_gender_name\":\"female\",\"endoscope_type\":null,\"endoscope_sn\":null,\"patient_hash_display\":\"...d426e9a5\",\"examination_hash_display\":\"...56258ef8\",\"pseudo_patient_id\":23,\"pseudo_examination_id\":65,\"examiners_display\":[\"Katarzyna Junk\",\"Abraham Löwer\"],\"is_verified\":false,\"dob_verified\":false,\"names_verified\":false,\"text\":\"Universitätsklinikum Würzburg\\nKlinikum der Bayerischen Julius-Maximilians-Universität\\nMedizinische Klinik und Poliklinik II\\nDirektor: Prof. Dr. H. Einsele\\nSchwerpunkt Gastroenterologie\\nLehrstuhlinhaber: Prof. Dr. A. Meining\\nMed. Klinik und Poliklinik II, ZIM\\nOberdürrbacher Str. 6-8, 97080 Würzburg\\nSCHWERPUNKT\\nGASTROENTEROLOGIE\\nCarla Marija Viktorija Franziska Gorse\\nProf. Dr. A. Meining\\nMedizinische Klinik II\\nSekretariat\\nOberdürrbacher Straße 6-8\\nFr.A. Weißenberger\\n97080 Würzburg Tel.0931 201-40201\\nEndoskopie\\nZIM Haus A4 Ebene -1\\nTel. 0931 201-40220\\nPatient: Kilian ,Claudia geb. 27.11.1971 Fallnummer: 0016501095\\nSchloßmühlstr. 2, 97294 Unterpleichfeld\\n1. Unters.: PD Dr. Reiter, Florian U-datum:29.01.2025 14:00\\n2.Unters.: PD Dr. Brand, Markus Assist.:Fischer, Jennifer, Purrer,\\nPD Dr. Mandy\\nBrand,\\nMarkus\\nIleokoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-EZ1500DL (SN 2000543)\\nAnamnese: Koloskopie 17.1.2025 (Internisten am Dominikaner-Platz):\\nAdenomrezidiv (vormals SSA) mit noch fest aufsitzend Hämoclip mit einem\\nDurchmesser von ca. 1,5 cm im Zökum\\nKeine Beschwerden, keine B-Symptomatik, keine familiäre Belastung für\\nDarmkrebs\\nIndikation: Polypektomie\\nPrämedikation: 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. Pulsoxymetrische- + Kreislaufüberwachung. 580 mg Propofol\\ni. v. (fraktioniert). Meropenem 1g unmittelbar nach Feststellung der Perforation.\\nMaximale Einsicht: Terminales Ileum.\\nAnus: Inspektion und Palpation unauffällig.\\nColon: BBPS 3+3+3\\nIm Bereich des Zökums findet sich das Restadenom mit Clip in situ (ca. 1,5cm, NICE II, Paris\\nIs). Der TTS Clip wird entfernt. Im Anschluss hebt sich die Schleimhaut unter\\nGlycerolsteril/Adrenalin adäquat ab. Das Restadenom wird unvollständig in drei\\nSchlingenhieben abgetragen. Nach dem dritten Schlingenschnitt zeigt sich ein 2 mm großes\\nPerforationsloch. Die Polypektomie, die unvollständig war, wird an dieser Stelle abgebrochen.\\nIm Anschluss erfolgt die Bespannung eines OTSC-Systems. Hierbei wird vorsichtig\\nvorgegangen und eine unnötige Luftinsufflation strikt vermieden. Dies gelingt. Die\\nPerforationsstelle kann zentral eingesaugt werden und makroskopisch adäquat und unter\\nleichter Saugung in der OTSC-Kappe mobilisiert und verschlossen werden.\\nHistologie: Restadenom Zökum\\nPatient: Kilian Claudia, geb. am 27.11.1971 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16501095 Untersuchung vom 29.01.2025\\n2002548627 14:00\\nBegutachtung:\\nDickdarmschleimhaut mit regelrechter Kryptenarchitektur und geringer chronischer\\nund florider Entzündung sowie reaktiven Epithelveränderungen. Anteile eines\\nAdenoms kommen nicht zur Darstellung (Restadenom Coecum, laut klinischen\\nAngaben). Kein Anhalt für Malignität.\\nKomplikation: ja 2mm Perforation bei EMR\\nBeurteilung\\nendgültig: Restadenom. Perforation im Rahmen der Polypektomie => Verschluss mittels\\nOTSC-Clip.\\nEmpfehlung: 1. Tägliches Infektlabor.\\n2. Stationäre Überwachung bis mindestens Freitag.\\n3. Bei Infektwertanstieg, Fieber oder Schmerzen umgehend CT.\\n4. Antibiose bis Freitag weiterführen, weitere Anpassung je nach Verlauf.\\n5. Heute nur Wasser.\\n6. Wiederholung in 3-6 Monaten zur Vervollständigung der Polypektomie, hier mittels FTRD.\\nAnmerkung: Die Histologie muss als nicht repräsentativ erachtet werden, da in Anbetracht der\\nAkutrversorgung die Bergung des gesamten Resektats nicht angestrebt bzw. durchgeführt\\nwurde. Makroskopisch besteht kein Zweifel an einem Adenom, dessen Abtragung im Verlauf\\nnoch vervollständigt werden muss.\\n___________________________ ___________________________\\nPD Dr. Reiter, Florian PD Dr. Brand, Markus\\nPatient: Kilian Claudia, geb. am 27.11.1971 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16501095 Untersuchung vom 29.01.2025\\n2002548627 14:00\",\"anonymized_text\":\"1. Unters.: PD Dr. Hövel, Alexandros U-datum:27.02.2025 14:00\\n2.Unters.: PD Dr. Hornig, Saban Assist.:Fischer, Jennifer, Hartmann,\\nPD Dr. Zeynep\\nHornig,\\nSaban\\nIleokoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-EZ1500DL (SN 8016434)\\nAnamnese: Koloskopie 17.1.2025 (Internisten am Dominikaner-Platz):\\nAdenomrezidiv (vormals SSA) mit noch fest aufsitzend Hämoclip mit einem\\nDurchmesser von ca. 1,5 cm im Zökum\\nKeine Beschwerden, keine B-Symptomatik, keine familiäre Belastung für\\nDarmkrebs\\nIndikation: Polypektomie\\nPrämedikation: 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. Pulsoxymetrische- + Kreislaufüberwachung. 580 mg Propofol\\ni. v. (fraktioniert). Meropenem 1g unmittelbar nach Feststellung der Perforation.\\nMaximale Einsicht: Terminales Ileum.\\nAnus: Inspektion und Palpation unauffällig.\\nColon: BBPS 3+3+3\\nIm Bereich des Zökums findet sich das Restadenom mit Clip in situ (ca. 1,5cm, NICE II, Paris\\nIs). Der TTS Clip wird entfernt. Im Anschluss hebt sich die Schleimhaut unter\\nGlycerolsteril/Adrenalin adäquat ab. Das Restadenom wird unvollständig in drei\\nSchlingenhieben abgetragen. Nach dem dritten Schlingenschnitt zeigt sich ein 2 mm großes\\nPerforationsloch. Die Polypektomie, die unvollständig war, wird an dieser Stelle abgebrochen.\\nIm Anschluss erfolgt die Bespannung eines OTSC-Systems. Hierbei wird vorsichtig\\nvorgegangen und eine unnötige Luftinsufflation strikt vermieden. Dies gelingt. Die\\nPerforationsstelle kann zentral eingesaugt werden und makroskopisch adäquat und unter\\nleichter Saugung in der OTSC-Kappe mobilisiert und verschlossen werden.\\nHistologie: Restadenom Zökum\\nPatient: Kilian Antonie, geb. am 27.11.1971 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 18188554 Untersuchung vom 27.02.2025\\n7835370193 14:00\\nBegutachtung:\\nDickdarmschleimhaut mit regelrechter Kryptenarchitektur und geringer chronischer\\nund florider Entzündung sowie reaktiven Epithelveränderungen. Anteile eines\\nAdenoms kommen nicht zur Darstellung (Restadenom Coecum, laut klinischen\\nAngaben). Kein Anhalt für Malignität.\\nKomplikation: ja 2mm Perforation bei EMR\\nBeurteilung\\nendgültig: Restadenom. Perforation im Rahmen der Polypektomie => Verschluss mittels\\nOTSC-Clip.\\nEmpfehlung: 1. Tägliches Infektlabor.\\n2. Stationäre Überwachung bis mindestens Freitag.\\n3. Bei Infektwertanstieg, Fieber oder Schmerzen umgehend CT.\\n4. Antibiose bis Freitag weiterführen, weitere Anpassung je nach Verlauf.\\n5. Heute nur Wasser.\\n6. Wiederholung in 3-6 Monaten zur Vervollständigung der Polypektomie, hier mittels FTRD.\\nAnmerkung: Die Histologie muss als nicht repräsentativ erachtet werden, da in Anbetracht der\\nAkutrversorgung die Bergung des gesamten Resektats nicht angestrebt bzw. durchgeführt\\nwurde. Makroskopisch besteht kein Zweifel an einem Adenom, dessen Abtragung im Verlauf\\nnoch vervollständigt werden muss.\\n___________________________ ___________________________\",\"tags\":[],\"validation_comment\":\"\",\"external_id\":null,\"external_id_origin\":null},{\"id\":19,\"casenumber\":\"0016529327\",\"patient_first_name\":\"Bettina\",\"patient_last_name\":\"unknown\",\"patient_dob\":\"1958-12-06T00:00:00-06:00\",\"patient_dob_display\":\"1958-12-06\",\"examination_date\":\"2025-02-19\",\"examination_date_display\":\"2025-02-19\",\"examination_time\":\"14:10:00\",\"center_name\":\"university_hospital_wuerzburg\",\"patient_gender_name\":\"female\",\"endoscope_type\":null,\"endoscope_sn\":null,\"patient_hash_display\":\"...ef26ad27\",\"examination_hash_display\":\"...5afbd942\",\"pseudo_patient_id\":22,\"pseudo_examination_id\":64,\"examiners_display\":[\"Katarzyna Junk\",\"Abraham Löwer\"],\"is_verified\":false,\"dob_verified\":false,\"names_verified\":false,\"text\":\"Universitätsklinikum Würzburg\\nKlinikum der Bayerischen Julius-Maximilians-Universität\\nMedizinische Klinik und Poliklinik II\\nDirektor: Prof. Dr. H. Einsele\\nSchwerpunkt Gastroenterologie\\nLehrstuhlinhaber: Prof. Dr. A. Meining\\nMed. Klinik und Poliklinik II, ZIM\\nOberdürrbacher Str. 6-8, 97080 Würzburg\\nSCHWERPUNKT\\nGASTROENTEROLOGIE\\nFriedrich Herder\\nProf. Dr. A. Meining\\nMedizinische Klinik II\\nSekretariat\\nOberdürrbacher Straße 6-8\\nFr.A. Weißenberger\\n97080 Würzburg Tel.0931 201-40201\\nEndoskopie\\nZIM Haus A4 Ebene -1\\nTel. 0931 201-40220\\nPatient: Dees ,Bettina geb. 12.06.1958 Fallnummer: 0016529327\\nUnterer Neubergweg 19a, 97074 Würzburg\\n1. Unters.: PD Dr. Reiter, Florian U-datum:19.02.2025 14:10\\nAssist.:Purrer, Mandy,\\nWiesemann, Hans\\nIleokoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-HQ190L (SN 2513804)\\nAnamnese: Zuletzt Koloskopie in domo bei Stuhlveränderungen, hier SSA im ascendens\\n(1,2-1,5 cm) auf einer Querfalte\\nIndikation: Abtragung\\nPrämedikation: 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. Pulsoxymetrische- + Kreislaufüberwachung. 440 mg Propofol\\ni. v. (fraktioniert).\\nMaximale Einsicht: Terminales Ileum.\\nColon: BBPS 3+3+3\\nEs zeigt sich eine Divertikulose mit mehreren Divertikeln ohne Lumeneinengung vor allem im\\nSigma. Es zeigt sich ein schmalbasiger Polyp im proximalen Colon ascendens mit einer Größe\\nvon 12 mm und intakter Oberfläche (Paris Is NICE I). Der Polyp wird nach einer Stielinfiltration\\nAdrenalin/Glycerosteril komplett in einem Stück entfernt und geborgen. Keine Komplikationen.\\nZur Prophylaxe Wundverschluss mit 1 Clip(s).\\nIm Rektosigmoid finden sich mehrere hyperplastische Polypen (NICE I, <1 cm). Zwei Polypen\\nmit einer NICE-II-Konfiguration (den vorbeschriebenen entsprechend) werden gemeinsam mit\\neinem Schlingenhieb in einem Resektat entfernt und geborgen. Die Stelle wird bei leichter\\nNachblutung mittels TTS-Clip verschlossen. Hiernach sistiert die Nachblutung.\\nEs zeigen sich mehrere aphthoide, stets paarweise auftretende Läsionen, die den Vorbiopsien\\nentsprechen.\\nHistologie:\\nKomplikation: nein\\nBeurteilung Divertikulose ohne Lumeneinengung im Sigma (K57.30).\\nvorläufig:\\nSessiler Polyp im proximalen Colon ascendens (D12.2) → Entfernung mittels Schlinge.\\nPatient: Dees Bettina, geb. am 12.06.1958 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16529327 Untersuchung vom 19.02.2025\\n2000103310 14:10\\nZwei Polypen im rektosigmoidalen Übergang → Entfernung mittels Schlinge.\\n=>\\nBlutungsprophylaxe beider Abtragungsstellen mittels TTS-Clip.\\nEmpfehlung: Die Empfehlung folgt nach Erhalt der Histologie. Heute Abend und morgen => Hb Kontrolle.\\n___________________________\\nPD Dr. Reiter, Florian\\nPatient: Dees Bettina, geb. am 12.06.1958 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16529327 Untersuchung vom 19.02.2025\\n2000103310 14:10\",\"anonymized_text\":\"1. Unters.: PD Dr. Trub, Lutz U-datum:20.01.2025 14:10\\nAssist.:Weinhold, Henner,\\nSäuberlichmann, Korinna\\nIleokoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-HQ190L (SN 7573957)\\nAnamnese: Zuletzt Koloskopie in domo bei Stuhlveränderungen, hier SSA im ascendens\\n(1,2-1,5 cm) auf einer Querfalte\\nIndikation: Abtragung\\nPrämedikation: 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. Pulsoxymetrische- + Kreislaufüberwachung. 440 mg Propofol\\ni. v. (fraktioniert).\\nMaximale Einsicht: Terminales Ileum.\\nColon: BBPS 3+3+3\\nEs zeigt sich eine Divertikulose mit mehreren Divertikeln ohne Lumeneinengung vor allem im\\nSigma. Es zeigt sich ein schmalbasiger Polyp im proximalen Colon ascendens mit einer Größe\\nvon 12 mm und intakter Oberfläche (Paris Is NICE I). Der Polyp wird nach einer Stielinfiltration\\nAdrenalin/Glycerosteril komplett in einem Stück entfernt und geborgen. Keine Komplikationen.\\nZur Prophylaxe Wundverschluss mit 1 Clip(s).\\nIm Rektosigmoid finden sich mehrere hyperplastische Polypen (NICE I, <1 cm). Zwei Polypen\\nmit einer NICE-II-Konfiguration (den vorbeschriebenen entsprechend) werden gemeinsam mit\\neinem Schlingenhieb in einem Resektat entfernt und geborgen. Die Stelle wird bei leichter\\nNachblutung mittels TTS-Clip verschlossen. Hiernach sistiert die Nachblutung.\\nEs zeigen sich mehrere aphthoide, stets paarweise auftretende Läsionen, die den Vorbiopsien\\nentsprechen.\\nHistologie:\\nKomplikation: nein\\nBeurteilung Divertikulose ohne Lumeneinengung im Sigma (K57.30).\\nvorläufig:\\nSessiler Polyp im proximalen Colon ascendens (D12.2) → Entfernung mittels Schlinge.\\nPatient: Dees Tillmann, geb. am 12.06.1958 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 41485677 Untersuchung vom 20.01.2025\\n7788709681 14:10\\nZwei Polypen im rektosigmoidalen Übergang → Entfernung mittels Schlinge.\\n=>\\nBlutungsprophylaxe beider Abtragungsstellen mittels TTS-Clip.\\nEmpfehlung: Die Empfehlung folgt nach Erhalt der Histologie. Heute Abend und morgen => Hb Kontrolle.\\n___________________________\",\"tags\":[],\"validation_comment\":\"\",\"external_id\":null,\"external_id_origin\":null},{\"id\":18,\"casenumber\":\"0016510726\",\"patient_first_name\":\"Jutta\",\"patient_last_name\":\"Günes\",\"patient_dob\":\"1959-06-08T00:00:00-05:00\",\"patient_dob_display\":\"1959-06-08\",\"examination_date\":\"2025-02-06\",\"examination_date_display\":\"2025-02-06\",\"examination_time\":\"14:50:00\",\"center_name\":\"university_hospital_wuerzburg\",\"patient_gender_name\":\"male\",\"endoscope_type\":null,\"endoscope_sn\":null,\"patient_hash_display\":\"...7ff0f7d4\",\"examination_hash_display\":\"...ed629149\",\"pseudo_patient_id\":21,\"pseudo_examination_id\":63,\"examiners_display\":[\"Katarzyna Junk\",\"Abraham Löwer\"],\"is_verified\":false,\"dob_verified\":false,\"names_verified\":false,\"text\":\"Universitätsklinikum Würzburg\\nKlinikum der Bayerischen Julius-Maximilians-Universität\\nMedizinische Klinik und Poliklinik II\\nDirektor: Prof. Dr. H. Einsele\\nSchwerpunkt Gastroenterologie\\nLehrstuhlinhaber: Prof. Dr. A. Meining\\nMed. Klinik und Poliklinik II, ZIM\\nOberdürrbacher Str. 6-8, 97080 Würzburg\\nSCHWERPUNKT\\nGASTROENTEROLOGIE\\nFriedrich Herder\\nProf. Dr. A. Meining\\nMedizinische Klinik II\\nSekretariat\\nOberdürrbacher Straße 6-8\\nFr.A. Weißenberger\\n97080 Würzburg Tel.0931 201-40201\\nEndoskopie\\nZIM Haus A4 Ebene -1\\nTel. 0931 201-40220\\nPatient: Günes ,Jutta geb. 06.08.1959 Fallnummer: 0016510726\\nRothmühlstr. 29, 97493 Bergrheinfeld\\n1. Unters.: PD Dr. Reiter, Florian U-datum:06.02.2025 14:50\\n2.Unters.: Sara De Monte Assist.:Sultan, Anja, Erichsen,\\nSara De Sarah\\nMonte\\nIleokoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-HQ190L (SN 2419349)\\nAnamnese: Bekannte Patientin, Polyposis coli\\nZuletzt Koloskopie bei unzureichend abgeführt am Darm abgebrochen\\nIndikation: Polypektomie\\nPrämedikation: 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. Pulsoxymetrische- + Kreislaufüberwachung. 420 mg Propofol\\ni. v. (fraktioniert).\\nMaximale Einsicht: Coecum.\\nColon: BBPS 3+3+3\\nEs finden sich unzählige Polypen bis 8 mm (alles NICE I und Paris Is). Alle sichtbaren Läsionen\\nwurden unter Verwendung der Cold-Snare zum Teil auch in Piece-Meal-Technik abgetragen.\\nHistologie:\\nKomplikation: nein\\nBeurteilung Abtragung von > 10 Polypen im Colon (alle <1cm).\\nendgültig:\\nEmpfehlung: In Anbetracht der Vielzahl der Polypen sollte eine Kontrolle spätestens in 1 Jahr erfolgen.\\n___________________________ ___________________________\\nPD Dr. Reiter, Florian Sara De Monte\\nPatient: Günes Jutta, geb. am 06.08.1959 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16510726 Untersuchung vom 06.02.2025\\n2002757549 14:50\\nPatient: Günes Jutta, geb. am 06.08.1959 Pat.Nr.: Fall.Nr.: 16510726 Untersuchung vom 06.02.2025\\n2002757549 14:50\",\"anonymized_text\":\"1. Unters.: PD Dr. Kallert, Ante U-datum:13.02.2025 14:50\\n2.Unters.: Sara De Monte Assist.:Sultan, Dorina, Erichsen,\\nSara De Sarah\\nMonte\\nIleokoloskopie\\nGerät: Olympus CF-HQ190L (SN 7009525)\\nAnamnese: Bekannte Patientin, Polyposis coli\\nZuletzt Koloskopie bei unzureichend abgeführt am Darm abgebrochen\\nIndikation: Polypektomie\\nPrämedikation: 3 l Sauerstoff über Nasensonde. Pulsoxymetrische- + Kreislaufüberwachung. 420 mg Propofol\\ni. v. (fraktioniert).\\nMaximale Einsicht: Coecum.\\nColon: BBPS 3+3+3\\nEs finden sich unzählige Polypen bis 8 mm (alles NICE I und Paris Is). Alle sichtbaren Läsionen\\nwurden unter Verwendung der Cold-Snare zum Teil auch in Piece-Meal-Technik abgetragen.\\nHistologie:\\nKomplikation: nein\\nBeurteilung Abtragung von > 10 Polypen im Colon (alle <1cm).\\nendgültig:\\nEmpfehlung: In Anbetracht der Vielzahl der Polypen sollte eine Kontrolle spätestens in 1 Jahr erfolgen.\\n___________________________ ___________________________\",\"tags\":[],\"validation_comment\":\"\",\"external_id\":null,\"external_id_origin\":null},{\"id\":17,\"casenumber\":\"f75\",\"patient_first_name\":\"EEZ\",\"patient_last_name\":\"MDE\",\"patient_dob\":\"2024-02-15T00:00:00-06:00\",\"patient_dob_display\":\"2024-02-15\",\"examination_date\":\"2024-02-15\",\"examination_date_display\":\"2024-02-15\",\"examination_time\":null,\"center_name\":\"university_hospital_wuerzburg\",\"patient_gender_name\":\"male\",\"endoscope_type\":null,\"endoscope_sn\":null,\"patient_hash_display\":\"...7c816a64\",\"examination_hash_display\":\"...3c1f61e5\",\"pseudo_patient_id\":20,\"pseudo_examination_id\":61,\"examiners_display\":[\"Katarzyna Junk\"],\"is_verified\":false,\"dob_verified\":false,\"names_verified\":false,\"text\":\"15/02/2024 09:50:10 A\\nM Lux, S\\nThomas , 21/03/1994 29\\nY 0 ; s\\n0 .0 d A1 I\\nul ,\\nEl Kommen\\ntar\\n. GIFEZ1500\\nEN 2001951 B\\nO 2.8 e .\\nO 9.9/9.6 d . Standbild ; 4 N Nl K . W TXI An Auslösen 1 x 4 e . f Fokus . R\\nN W da\\nN : 3\",\"anonymized_text\":null,\"tags\":[],\"validation_comment\":\"\",\"external_id\":null,\"external_id_origin\":null},{\"id\":16,\"casenumber\":null,\"patient_first_name\":\"unknown\",\"patient_last_name\":\"unknown\",\"patient_dob\":\"1970-01-01T00:00:00-06:00\",\"patient_dob_display\":\"1970-01-01\",\"examination_date\":\"2026-04-21\",\"examination_date_display\":\"2026-04-21\",\"examination_time\":null,\"center_name\":\"university_hospital_wuerzburg\",\"patient_gender_name\":\"unknown\",\"endoscope_type\":null,\"endoscope_sn\":null,\"patient_hash_display\":\"...835c0a39\",\"examination_hash_display\":\"...9e9a0349\",\"pseudo_patient_id\":17,\"pseudo_examination_id\":59,\"examiners_display\":[\"Katarzyna Junk\"],\"is_verified\":false,\"dob_verified\":false,\"names_verified\":false,\"text\":\"NASA-TLX Fragebogen (Interaktiv)\\nAngepasste Software-Evaluation (Raw-TLX, 5 Faktoren)\\nAnleitung: Bitte bewerten Sie die Aufgabe. Klicken Sie auf den entsprechenden Kreis (Skala 1-20).\\nGeistige Anforderungen\\nDenken, Entscheiden, Suchen, etc.\\nGering Hoch\\nZeitliche Anforderungen\\nZeitdruck, Takt der Aufgabe\\nGering Hoch\\nEigene Leistung\\nErfolg bei der Erledigung der Ziele\\nGut Schlecht\\nAnstrengung\\nGeistiger Arbeitsaufwand\\nGering Hoch\\nFrustrationsniveau\\nStress, Irritation, Verärgerung\\nGering Hoch\\nZusätzliche Anmerkungen\",\"anonymized_text\":\"NASA-TLX Fragebogen (Interaktiv)\\nAngepasste Software-Evaluation (Raw-TLX, 5 Faktoren)\\nAnleitung: Bitte bewerten Sie die Aufgabe. Klicken Sie auf den entsprechenden Kreis (Skala 1-20).\\nGeistige Anforderungen\\nDenken, Entscheiden, Suchen, etc.\\nGering Hoch\\nZeitliche Anforderungen\\nZeitdruck, Takt der Aufgabe\\nGering Hoch\\nEigene Leistung\\nErfolg bei der Erledigung der Ziele\\nGut Schlecht\\nAnstrengung\\nGeistiger Arbeitsaufwand\\nGering Hoch\\nFrustrationsniveau\\nStress, Irritation, Verärgerung\\nGering Hoch\\nZusätzliche Anmerkungen\",\"tags\":[],\"validation_comment\":\"\",\"external_id\":null,\"external_id_origin\":null},{\"id\":15,\"casenumber\":null,\"patient_first_name\":\"and\",\"patient_last_name\":\"care\",\"patient_dob\":\"1970-01-01T00:00:00-06:00\",\"patient_dob_display\":\"1970-01-01\",\"examination_date\":\"2026-04-16\",\"examination_date_display\":\"2026-04-16\",\"examination_time\":null,\"center_name\":\"university_hospital_wuerzburg\",\"patient_gender_name\":\"unknown\",\"endoscope_type\":null,\"endoscope_sn\":null,\"patient_hash_display\":\"...9dfee7f3\",\"examination_hash_display\":\"...11c055f9\",\"pseudo_patient_id\":19,\"pseudo_examination_id\":58,\"examiners_display\":[\"Katarzyna Junk\"],\"is_verified\":false,\"dob_verified\":false,\"names_verified\":false,\"text\":\"Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\nAn Entry-Validated Data Model for Consistent Clinical Data\\nCapture and Interoperability\\nJournal: Methods of Information in Medicine\\nManuscript ID Draft\\nF\\nManuscript Type: Original Article\\no\\nstandardization, standardized terminology, quality improvement,\\nKeywords: r\\nendoscopy, health information interoperability\\nP\\ne\\nNote: The following files were submitted by the author for peer review, but cannot be converted to\\nPDF. You must view these files (e.g. moviees) online.\\nSupplementary File 1 - pyproject.toml r\\nSupplementary File 3 - usage_example.py\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 1 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\nAn Entry‑Validated Data Model for Consistent Clinical Data\\n1\\nCapture and Interoperability\\n2\\n3 Authors: Thomas J. Lux1*, Peter Kowalczyk1, Max Hild1, Syed Muhammad Hamza\\n4 Zahid1, Clara Wirsing1, Alexander Meining1\\n5\\n6 1: University Hospital Würzburg, Internal Medicine II, Gastroenterology\\n7 *: corresponding author\\n8\\n9 Corresponding Author: Dr. med. M. Sc. Thomas J. Lux\\n10\\nF\\n11 University Hospital Würzburg, Internal Medicine II, Gastroenterology\\no\\n12 Oberdürrbacher Str. 6, 97080 Würzburg, Germany\\n13 Phone: +49 931 201-40247r\\n14 Mail: lux_t1@ukw.de\\nP\\n15 Fax: +49 931 201 640201\\ne\\n16\\ne\\n17 Keywords: standardization, standardized terminology, quality improvement, endoscopy,\\nr\\n18 Health Information Interoperability R\\ne\\n19\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 2 of 42\\n1 Structured Abstract\\n2 Background: Reuse of clinical data for quality assurance, research, and artificial\\n3 intelligence (AI) critically depends on internal consistency and interpretability of data.\\n4 Despite widespread adoption of interoperability standards such as HL7-FHIR, DICOM,\\n5 and SNOMED CT, many clinical systems rely on heterogeneous internal data\\n6 representations including narrative reports. Existing standards enable syntactic exchange\\n7 and semantic encodinFg; they don’t define how data should be logically structured or supply\\no\\n8 context for interpretation which often evolves over time.\\nr\\n9 Objectives: We aim to develoPp a framework supporting medical knowledge modelling\\ne\\n10 and data management to improve interpretability of datasets independent of time and\\ne\\n11 location. For this we envision a strongrly typed data model and associated knowledge-\\nR\\n12 base to enforce consistent, uniform and interpretable datasets. The framework should be\\ne\\n13 domain-agnostic and use a configurable, versioned KnowledgeBase.\\nv\\ni\\n14 Methods: Using upper gastrointestinal endoscopy reeporting as a reference application,\\nw\\n15 we extracted reporting standards from the European Standardization of Reports initiative.\\n16 Those were operationalized to guide data completeness and consistency at entry time. A\\n17 custom Python package was developed to satisfy those requirements utilizing existing\\n18 Python-Packages (Pydantic for type validation; Django for providing an application\\n19 programming interface).\\n20 Results: With the developed software package, datasets can be created, maintained,\\n21 stored, and exchanged as structured files and SQL database objects. Each dataset stores\\n22 a medical KnowledgeBase as context for interpretation. We created a demo dataset\\n23 featuring a KnowledgeBase derived from the European recommendations for gastroscopy\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 3 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 reporting. The developed Software was published (GitHub, PyPI) and can be installed in\\n2 Python projects for immediate community use and development.\\n3 Conclusions: The proposed published framework shifts data quality assurance from\\n4 retrospective curation to prospective enforcement. It provides an extensible, open-source\\n5 foundation for analytics- and AI-ready clinical data across domains.\\n6\\nF\\n7\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 4 of 42\\n1 1. Introduction\\n2 Structured Reporting and Interoperability in Medical Data Processing\\n3 Clinical documentation is the primary interface between patient care and digital health\\n4 infrastructure. Increasingly, primary clinical data is expected to support secondary use\\n5 cases, including quality assurance (QA), learning healthcare systems, epidemiological\\n6 research and evaluation, or the application of artificial intelligence 1,2. However, these\\nF\\n7 secondary uses require complete, logically consistent, and comparably structured data\\no\\n8 across time and institutions. The definition and assessment of primary clinical data’s\\nr\\n9 quality is a highly active reseParch subject without clear consensus yet3,4. Dimensions\\ne\\n10 relevant for our work are briefly introduced in the context of the European Society of\\ne\\n11 Gastrointestinal Endoscopy’s (ESGE) rrecommendations for STAndardization of Reports\\nR\\n12 (STAR) in upper gastrointestinal endoscopy5:\\ne\\n13 1. Completeness: Is all expected informationv explicitly available?\\ni\\n14 o Normal findings like “inconspicuous stomach mucosa” must be stated\\ne\\n15 explicitly\\nw\\n16 o Requirements to achieve “completeness” are dynamic; For example, the\\n17 size of a polyp influences what information should be reported\\n18 2. Consistency: Are any factual or logical constraints violated?\\n19 o Are classifications used in the correct context?\\n20 3. Stability\\n21 o Is the report comparable among sources and over time?\\n22\\n23 In practice, these prerequisites are frequently violated. Even in highly digitized\\n24 environments, clinical data entry often remains loosely constrained due to the complexity\\n25 and required flexibility6. Optional fields, free‑text descriptions, and ambiguous internal\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 5 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 representations lead to heterogeneous datasets that require extensive post‑hoc cleaning\\n2 and normalization7. These challenges are particularly pronounced in procedural domains,\\n3 where documentation combines structured measurements, categorical assessments,\\n4 narrative interpretation, and media references. Therefore, interoperability standards play\\n5 a critical role in enabling communication between systems to mitigate this hurdle8.\\n6 Interoperability: Data Entry, Persistence, and Exchange\\nF\\n7 While statistical data analysis often operates on tabular data, established data standards\\no\\n8 like FHIR operate on nested objects9. Figure 1 illustrates data of a patient with an\\nr\\n9 examination in tabular (left) anPd nested (right) representations. Both representations are\\ne\\n10 relevant: Tabular data has benefits regarding human readability and analytical purposes\\ne\\n11 whereas most digital applications rerly on nested objects during processing. As\\nR\\n12 consequence data is frequently transformed between these representations.\\ne\\n13 In this context, relationships between data pointsv as well as their representation are highly\\ni\\n14 relevant. For example, the nested patient represeentation in Figure 1 contains two\\nw\\n15 complete examination objects. In the tabular representation, this relationship is expressed\\n16 by adding the corresponding PatientID in each examination row. The interested reader\\n17 can find an overview of common data relationships in the context of relational databases\\n18 in Supplementary Information 1.\\n19\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 6 of 42\\n1 Serialization\\n2 Serialization is commonly referred to as the process of converting complex data structures\\n3 into a format that can be easily stored, transmitted and reconstructed by a different\\n4 system. Simplified, this translation can be broken down as follows:\\n5 1. Source: An electronic health record is created or modified using a graphical user\\n6 interface; the object now exists in the internal storage of the corresponding\\n7 application\\n8 2. Mapping: The source system requires exact instructions on how to translate the\\nF\\n9 internal representation so that the target system can import it\\no\\n10 3. Encoding: The translated data is stored as text or binary file\\nr\\n11\\nP\\n12 While seemingly straightforward,e the mapping between different data models requires\\ne\\n13 developers to make multiple decisions: Which fields are optional? Which unit is used for\\nr\\n14 numeric values? Which encoding is used for time-data (including time zone\\nR\\ne\\n15 configuration)? How should categorical values be represented?\\nv\\n16 Inhomogeneous assumptions in this process highily degrade our ability to merge and\\ne\\n17 analyze datasets from different origins. To ensure interwpretability, such decisions should\\n18 be well-documented, standardized and reproducible. Since medical expert consensus is\\n19 rarely accompanied by a machine-readable digital representation, this task is redundantly\\n20 performed by local IT departments, commercial software providers or research groups –\\n21 often with highly variable outcomes.\\n22\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 7 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 Relevance and Current State of Structured Reporting\\n2 Efforts toward structured clinical documentation have a long history, ranging from minimal\\n3 standard terminology initiatives10 to vendor‑specific templates and document‑centric\\n4 standards11. More recently, professional societies have emphasized structured reporting\\n5 as a prerequisite for quality assurance and comparability5. Anyhow, evolution of medical\\n6 knowledge as well as recommendations which may vary depending on local\\n7 circumstances / guidelines inhibit widespread adoption of suggested solutions12.\\nF\\no\\n8 At the same time, interoperability standards have matured significantly. FHIR, in\\nr\\n9 particular, has lowered the baPrrier for data exchange and integration 13. Anyhow, the\\ne\\n10 flexibility that makes these standards broadly applicable also limits their ability to enforce\\ne\\n11 strict data entry constraints 14. While this\\nr\\nsatisfies the necessary condition of data transfer,\\nR\\n12 it does not address the interpretation of the content12. Therefore, interoperability at a data\\ne\\n13 center level still requires intensive data processing to allow interpretation and meaningful\\nv\\n14 analysis. Use-case specific implementation guidesi can narrow this flexibility, but they do\\ne\\n15 not replace the need for coherent internal data represewntation. Inconsistent or false data\\n16 debilitates the usefulness of data for research and categorial analysis.\\n17 Medical consensus publications like the European recommendations for gastroscopy\\n18 reporting5 address such shortcomings but are provided as narrative text documents\\n19 without specifications for the digital representation of data. For example, the German\\n20 minimal standard terminology for gastrointestinal endoscopy consists of a ~260 page\\n21 document and provides excellent guidance for physicians. Anyhow, adherence in\\n22 reporting software or study protocols requires individual adoption for each application. In\\n23 consequence, data analysts and commercial reporting software providers are required to\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 8 of 42\\n1 derive individual solutions causing inhomogeneous datasets before they are parsed into\\n2 common interoperability standards.\\n3 Digital Interoperability vs. Medical Interoperability\\n4 Stored medical data serves multiple purposes depending on the context. This includes\\n5 medical communication, legal proof, billing with high priority as well as QA, and research.\\n6 Since narrative text reports technically fulfill legal and medical purposes, they are widely\\n7 used in healthcare proFviders’ IT systems. Anyhow, narrative reports lack standardization,\\no\\n8 availability and interpretability which are essential for QA and research. Since patient care\\nr\\n9 takes precedence over QA anPd research, acceptance of structured reporting is often\\ne\\n10 drastically lowered if it increases the documentation workload.\\ne\\n11 The interpretability of primary healthcarre data for secondary purposes is often decided\\nR\\n12 during creation. Anyhow, without guidance during report creation, narrative reporting\\ne\\n13 relies on the author’s knowledge to use terminology in the correct context and use scores\\nv\\ni\\n14 and classifications when appropriate. e\\nw\\n15 Deferring data quality control to retrospective validation and curation is resource‑intensive\\n16 and inherently limited. What is missing is a canonical internal data model that enforces\\n17 correctness, completeness, and logical structure based on medical recommendations at\\n18 the very moment of data capture.\\n19 2. Objectives\\n20 In this work, we propose an entry‑validated canonical data model designed to address\\n21 this gap and improve stability and consistency of clinical data: “Layered Extraction Data\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 9 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 Model” (LXDM). Rather than defining another domain‑specific exchange format, the\\n2 framework introduces a generic internal representation of medical datasets consisting of\\n3 actual data and an underlying medical KnowledgeBase. Consecutively, we demonstrate\\n4 how this framework can be applied on the recently published recommendations for\\n5 standardized reporting in upper gastrointestinal endoscopy by the European Society of\\n6 Gastrointestinal Endoscopy5.\\n7 To establish stable aFnd consistent interpretability of generated records, the framework\\no\\n8 implements scalable digitization of medical expert consensus into a KnowledgeBase\\nr\\n9 which is utilized for validatio n. Interoperability standards are treated as downstream\\nP\\n10 targets that operate on already vaelidated, consistently structured data. At its core, LXDM\\ne\\n11 should separate structure, semantics, and governance.\\nr\\nR\\n12 Structural consistency should be enforced through strongly typed model primitives.\\ne\\n13 Domain semantics, the responsibility of medical experts, are introduced through an\\nv\\ni\\n14 independently managed, versioned KnowledgeBase and referenced via stable identifiers.\\ne\\nw\\n15 Governance is supported through explicit provenance metadata and traceable concept\\n16 definitions embedded in the KnowledgeBase.\\n17 Domain & System Independence\\n18 The data structure and should allow implementation of different domain-specific\\n19 KnowledgeBase modules (e.g., endoscopy, computer-tomography or coronary\\n20 angiography) and allow for re-use of components across similar use cases. Serialization\\n21 should be treated as an explicit, first-class responsibility of internal persistence: Validated\\n22 canonical objects are transformed into uniform, system-independent representations prior\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 10 of 42\\n1 to storage preventing that application-specific data structures leak implicit assumptions\\n2 into persisted data.\\n3 Community Focus\\n4 Publication of a new data model itself is unlikely to achieve widespread adoption.\\n5 Therefore, the framework itself must provide meaningful incentives for different user\\n6 groups.\\nF\\n7 Publication of a ready-to-use Python package primarily addresses clinically focused data\\no\\n8 analysts in academic research. A well-tested and system-independent software package\\nr\\nP\\n9 potentially reduces the workload associated with data processing, management and\\ne\\n10 sharing. Availability of the source code on GitHub allows developers to publicly contribute\\ne\\n11 or privately adapt our framework. De-rcoupling of the domain specific KnowledgeBase\\nR\\n12 from the underlying code allows contribution and content moderation by medical experts\\ne\\n13 with no prior technical knowledge.\\nv\\ni\\ne\\n14 Medical Content Moderation\\nw\\n15 While the data model itself should be domain independent, it must allow the\\n16 implementation of use-case specific limitations (e.g., “Which findings are available for a\\n17 specific examination?”). The implemented knowledge (KnowledgeBase) should be\\n18 maintainable by medical specialists without specific IT training. Relationships between\\n19 objects (e.g., Examination  Findings) should be declared using readable, unique text\\n20 identifiers.\\n21\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 11 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 3. Methods\\n2 Software\\n3 The framework was developed using the Python programming language. Core models\\n4 were implemented using Pydantic (>=2.10.6) using the provided functionalities to enforce\\n5 validation and supply consistent serialization. Core models were mirrored using Django\\n6 (>=6.0) using the provided functionalities for interaction with relational databases. The\\nF\\n7 complete list of software dependencies is provided as supplementary file (SF1\\no\\n8 “pyproject.toml”). The pyproject format follows established conventions and can be used\\nr\\n9 to replicate the exact developmPent and production environment.\\ne\\n10 Objectification of Upper GI Endosecopy Report Recommendations\\nr\\n11 Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy was us ed as a reference to illustrate how LXDM can be\\nR\\n12 instantiated for a concrete clinical domain. Eeuropean recommendations5 were reviewed\\nv\\n13 to plan their digital representation in an exemplary KnowledgeBase.\\ni\\ne\\n14 KnowledgeBase Conceptualization w\\n15 Recommended report elements define which information elements are required or\\n16 recommended for a complete endoscopy report, including procedural context,\\n17 examination extent, findings, interventions, and complications. Those were generalized to\\n18 establish unbiased data classes without any explicit medical knowledge. The scope was\\n19 reduced to extracted findings (e.g. “Polyp”), corresponding classifications (e.g. “Paris 0-\\n20 Is”) and numeric descriptors (e.g. distances in cm). The Paris classification is commonly\\n21 to describe the morphology of superficial neoplastic lesions in the digestive tract15.\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 12 of 42\\n1 Consecutively, the previously established domain specific knowledge was solidified in\\n2 data fixtures which can populate the previously established generic data models.\\n3 Ethical Considerations\\n4 As neither human nor animal subjects were involved in this research, ethical review was\\n5 not required.\\n6\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 13 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 4. Results\\n2 LXDM is publicly available as ready-to-use Python package (https://pypi.org/project/lx-\\n3 dtypes/ ) and as code-repository for development ( https://github.com/wg-lux/lx-data-\\n4 models ). The published module features extensive test coverage to improve\\n5 maintainability and improve developer experience. Additionally, the available tests provide\\n6 usage examples for all core data classes including instantiation and serialization. This\\n7 publication referenceFs version 0.1.1 of the LXDM module and does not cover all\\no\\n8 implemented features and functionalities which are under continuous development. We\\nr\\n9 encourage interested readers to review the in-depth technical documentation available on\\nP\\n10 GitHub. e\\ne\\n11 Data Model Overview r\\nR\\n12 The canonical data model is based on a small set of generic structural primitives (models)\\ne\\n13 for consolidation of medical concepts and persivstence of patient related records. Actual\\ni\\n14 data-points (objects) are created by providing medicael knowledge or patient data to these\\nw\\n15 generic models. Patient-related objects are constructed in a logically coherent manner by\\n16 referencing previously established knowledge-related objects to provide a stable context.\\n17 These primitives are intentionally minimal and stable, allowing them to be reused across\\n18 domains while supporting strict validation and extensibility.\\n19 Attributes describe properties of models and are associated with explicit data types and\\n20 validation rules. Relationships encode how models are linked and provide traceability and\\n21 guarantee contextual interpretation. Table 1 summarizes the minimal technical\\n22 vocabulary.\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 14 of 42\\n1 The DbInterface Class\\n2 Our database tables are derived from object-oriented python classes. These form a\\n3 conceptual ontology, with each class containing specific validation and serialization\\n4 functions as well as links to related classes. The core component of our data model is the\\n5 DbInterface model which contains nested KnowledgeBase objects for generic concepts\\n6 and Ledger objects for patient related records (Figure 2).\\n7 After initialization, theF KnowledgeBase stores domain-specific medical knowledge. The\\no\\n8 KnowledgeBase defines controlled vocabulary, classification systems and permissible\\nr\\n9 units. To represent this, we implemented the following models: Examination, Finding,\\nP\\n10 Classification, ClassificationChoicee, ClassificationChoiceDescriptor, and Unit.\\ne\\n11 The Ledger stores patient-related obrjects which always reference KnowledgeBase\\nR\\n12 objects when required using the following models: Center, Examiner, Patient,\\ne\\n13 PatientExamination, PatientFinding, PatientFindingClassifications,\\nv\\ni\\n14 PatientFindingClassificationChoice, and PatientFindingClassificationChoiceDescriptor.\\ne\\nw\\n15 All objects initialized from KnowledgeBase or Ledger models carry a mandatory internal\\n16 identifier. Objects in the KnowledgeBase use a unique “name” attribute to ease readability\\n17 during medical content creation and moderation. The names are stable and unambiguous\\n18 within the scope of the KnowledgeBase. Objects in the Ledger are always generated by\\n19 the system and use UUIDs unique identifiers (UUID 4).\\n20 KnowledgeBaseConfig Modules & DataLoader\\n21 By design, the software itself does not contain explicit knowledge. Domain specific\\n22 knowledge is supplied in the form of KnowledgeBaseConfig modules. These modules are\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 15 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 specifically structured folders containing the modules configuration (name, dependencies,\\n2 child modules, version) and text files (yaml format) containing the actual information. The\\n3 KnowledgeBase modules are designed to be shared, re-used, and extended as required\\n4 by ever-changing medical knowledge and guidelines. The minimal structure of a\\n5 KnowledgeBaseConfig file and an exemplary implementation are demonstrated in Figure\\n6 3.\\n7 The DataLoader model imports KnowledgeBaseConfig files to instantiate a\\nF\\no\\n8 KnowledgeBase with the files supplied in the “data” fields. These files are supplied in the\\nr\\n9 yaml format and contain data fixtures. Data fixtures always contain a value for the “model”\\nP\\n10 attribute to define the target modeel (e.g., finding) and a value for the “name” attribute to\\ne\\n11 provide the unique identifier. Other fields depend on the target model: For example, data\\nr\\n12 fixtures for Finding objects expect a list of name identifiers for the “classifications” attribute\\nR\\ne\\n13 to define related Classification objects. KnowledgeBaseConfig Modules are loaded\\nv\\n14 deterministically, with explicit resolution of module dependencies. This ensures\\ni\\ne\\n15 reproducible model behavior and prevents hidden ordering assumptions or circular\\nw\\n16 dependencies. The relevant models including their location in the source code are\\n17 summarized Table 2.\\n18\\n19 Patient Record Construction\\n20 All creation of patient-related objects is mediated by the DbInterface containing an\\n21 initialized KnowledgeBase. Validation occurs at multiple levels, including schema\\n22 validation (e.g., data types), semantic validation (references exist in the KnowledgeBase),\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 16 of 42\\n1 and consistency checks (linked references are allowed via corresponding links in the\\n2 KnowledgeBase).\\n3 Persisted objects are stored without transformation, guaranteeing that data validated at\\n4 entry remain structured identically at rest. The complete dataset including the nested\\n5 KnowledgeBase and Ledger objects can be exported into a singular file utilizing the\\n6 “model_dump” method. Such exported datasets can be re-imported using the DbInterface\\n7 models “from_yaml” method. Capturing the KnowledgeBase used at creation time\\nF\\no\\n8 ensures full auditability and reproducibility across contexts, systems and versions.\\nr\\n9 Guideline Derived KnowledgPeBase for Upper GI Endoscopy Reporting\\ne\\n10 We implemented the KnowledgeBaseConfig module “star_upper_gi” with the Examination\\ne\\n11 “star_upper_gi_endoscopy“ (gastroscorpy) and the associated Findings, Classifications,\\nR\\n12 ClassificationChoices, and ClassificationChoiceDescriptors. Figure 4 demonstrates data\\ne\\n13 fixtures used to implement the Paris classification for the Finding polyp. The fully\\nv\\ni\\n14 implemented KnowledgeBaseConfig including aell data fixtures is available as\\nw\\n15 Supplementary Files SF2. While many descriptive features can be represented using\\n16 ClassificationChoices (e.g., polyp shape - “star_upper_gi_paris_Ip”), others require a non-\\n17 categorical input (e.g.,” size_oval_mm“ or “distance_cm”).\\n18 The resulting KnowledgeBaseConfig “star_upper_gi” contains a total of 22 findings, 21\\n19 classifications, 71 classification choices and 3 classification choice descriptors\\n20 (Supplementary Table 1). Additionally, a separate KnowledgeBaseConfig module named\\n21 „lx_units“ provides 41 Unit data fixtures including length (e.g., centimeter and millimeter)\\n22 and time (e.g., seconds and minutes) metrics.\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 17 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1\\n2 The patient-related Ledger object representing a performed upper gastrointestinal\\n3 endoscopy is represented as PatientExamination object. The nested PatientFinding\\n4 objects represent discrete observations made during the procedure. Patient specific\\n5 objects are linked to corresponding KnowledgeBase objects where appropriate (e.g.,\\n6 PatientExamination A points to Examination “star_upper_gi_endoscopy”). Similarly,\\n7 PatientFindings are linked to Findings in the KnowledgeBase (PatientFinding A points to\\nF\\no\\n8 Finding with name “star_upper_gi_polyp”). When adding a PatientFinding to a\\nr\\n9 PatientExamination, it can o nly point to Findings which are related to its parents\\nP\\n10 Examination in the KnowledgeeBase. Following this structure, Findings in the\\ne\\n11 KnowledgeBase are related to Classifications (e.g., “star_upper_gi_lesion_paris”).\\nr\\n12 An example of usage in the form of a PRython script is provided in the supplements\\ne\\n13 (Supplementary File 3). The example demonstrates how the published Python module\\nv\\n14 can be used to import the KnowledgeBaseConfig (iSupplementary File 2), create patient\\ne\\n15 records and finally export the complete dataset. w\\n16 While upper gastrointestinal endoscopy serves as a concrete illustration, the principles\\n17 demonstrated in this case example are not specific to endoscopy. Any clinical domain in\\n18 which professional standards define reporting requirements, but lack enforceable entry-\\n19 level constraints, can be instantiated using the same approach. Domain adaptation\\n20 primarily involves extending the KnowledgeBase, rather than modifying the canonical\\n21 model itself.\\n22\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 18 of 42\\n1\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 19 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 5. Discussion\\n2 This work reframes data quality, including context provision, as an entry-level problem\\n3 rather than an exchange-level or post-hoc harmonization problem. To address this, we\\n4 developed and published a Python package (LXDM) including comprehensive\\n5 documentation and testing.\\n6 Interoperability of clinical data is highly relevant to enable large scale data analysis like\\nF\\n7 development of artificial intelligence models. Meaningful utilization of data relies on data\\no\\n8 quality and interpretability. While data standards and exchange formats like FHIR and\\nr\\n9 DICOM are steadily improving Pand allow for large scale exchange of information, they are\\ne\\n10 not designed to prevent incomplete, inconsistent, or weakly structured data from being\\ne\\n11 created in the first place which may caurse datasets to be analytically fragile. This problem\\nR\\n12 is exacerbated as evolving medical knowledge and recommendations may re-frame\\ne\\n13 previously generated data. As consequence, exchanged data often requires manual\\nv\\ni\\n14 processing to match context and expectations of the user before it can be properly\\ne\\nw\\n15 interpreted.\\n16 Our framework, LXDM, aims to mitigate this issue by enforcing logical consistency with a\\n17 sharable versionable and self-contained KnowledgeBase at the moment of instantiation:\\n18 To improve interpretability, stability and comparability of datasets, we emphasized the\\n19 problem of context provision in this work. An important design decision to achieve this\\n20 was the externalization of domain semantics and usage logic. Examinations, findings,\\n21 classifications, and their dependencies are treated as governed content rather than as\\n22 hard-coded elements of the data model. This architectural choice allows the internal\\n23 representation to remain stable while domain knowledge can evolve over time. This\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 20 of 42\\n1 clearly defines the implementation of medical knowledge as responsibility of medical\\n2 experts and separates it from managing data itself. As consequence, medical\\n3 professionals may focus on creating and evolving the KnowledgeBase whereas data\\n4 analysts and software engineers are not required to interpret and implement narrative\\n5 recommendations into data models, relations and user interfaces.\\n6 Controlled curation of this KnowledgeBase is essential to maintain comparability across\\n7 sites and over time. Without such governance, uncontrolled extensions could reintroduce\\nF\\no\\n8 heterogeneity at the semantic level, even if structural consistency is preserved. A\\nr\\n9 complementary line of work is therefore required to address terminology management\\nP\\n10 itself as a first-class technical coencern. In future, guidelines could be accompanied by\\ne\\n11 KnowledgeBase modules to assert such governance.\\nr\\n12 R\\ne\\n13 Clinical & Public Health Implications v\\ni\\ne\\n14 The published software aims to benefit several user groups:\\nw\\n15 Data analysts can streamline their data processing by using the readily available python\\n16 package. An usage example in form of a Python script and setup instructions is provided\\n17 in the supplements (Supplementary File 3). Industrial developers and publishers of\\n18 guidelines profit from the standardized KnowledgeBase to harmonize published\\n19 terminologies as well as their digital representation. Researchers and experts of other\\n20 domains may contribute, re-use or alter customize the publicly available code (\\n21 https://github.com/wg-lux/lx-data-models ).\\n22\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 21 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 Using upper gastrointestinal endoscopy as a reference application, we could showcase\\n2 the implementation of a KnowledgeBase. Anyhow, the framework is not specific to this\\n3 domain. Many clinical areas face similar challenges, particularly where professional\\n4 societies define reporting requirements but lack guidance to create shareable,\\n5 maintainable digital representations without in-depth technical knowledge of data\\n6 structures. Examples include pathology reporting16, procedural documentation5, and\\n7 structured clinical assessments. Existing literature mostly focuses on textual definitions\\nF\\n8 and defers the task of diogital representation to IT specialists often resulting in redundant,\\nr\\n9 inconsistent and unmaintained implementations.\\nP\\n10 e\\ne\\n11 Limitations\\nr\\nR\\n12 Currently, creation or modification of the database modules requires editing raw text file\\ne\\n13 in the “yaml” format. In theory, this can be done with every text editor and on every\\nv\\ni\\n14 operating system. Anyhow, users are required to adheere to the file syntax as even simple\\nw\\n15 indentation issues may render files “unreadable” for the DataLoader. In future, we are\\n16 planning to address this issue by publishing a web-application to create and edit\\n17 KnowledgeBaseConfig modules.\\n18 While the published package is thoroughly tested, unexpected issues may arise when\\n19 extending the framework to new domains. We tried to mitigate this risk by adhering to\\n20 strict typing and linting standards during the development. As consequence, developers\\n21 can fully utilize their development environments helper functions during error tracing.\\n22\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 22 of 42\\n1 Outlook\\n2 Future work will focus on formal evaluation of data quality improvements enabled by entry-\\n3 level validation, including comparative analyses against loosely constrained\\n4 documentation approaches. Further extensions include implementation of Intervention\\n5 and Indication models as well as video and image file support to extend the usability of\\n6 the framework. Furthermore, we are currently planning a FHIR compliant export of patient-\\n7 related data stored in the Ledger and deeper integration with AI pipelines through\\nF\\n8 standardized, reproducibole linkage between structured clinical data and associated media.\\nr\\n9 In the long term, extension and maintenance of KnowledgeBaseConfig modules focused\\nP\\n10 on gastrointestinal endoscopy coeuld relief researchers of data model development and\\ne\\n11 management tasks allowing them to focus on their actual research. We strongly believe,\\nr\\n12 that our framework poses a significaRnt first step to decrease workload while\\ne\\n13 simultaneously improving data interoperability.\\nv\\ni\\n14\\ne\\nw\\n15 6. Conclusions\\n16 In conclusion, we presented an entry-validated canonical data model designed to ensure\\n17 correct data capture, logical consistency, and uniform persistence as a prerequisite for\\n18 interoperability. By decoupling internal structure from exchange standards and\\n19 externalizing domain semantics into a governed KnowledgeBase, the framework provides\\n20 a robust and generalizable foundation for high-quality clinical data reuse. In combination\\n21 with structured, executable terminology management, this approach offers a pathway\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 23 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 toward reproducible, auditable, and AI-ready clinical datasets across domains as the\\n2 demand for reproducible, AI-ready clinical data continues to grow.\\n3 Acknowledgements\\n4 This work was funded by the Gastroenterology Foundation, Zürich (Project: ColoReg\\n5 Trial).\\n6\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 24 of 42\\n1 References\\n2 1. Meystre SM; L C; Bürkle, T; Tognola, G; Budrionis, A; Lehmann, CU. Clinical Data Reuse or\\n3 Secondary Use: Current Status and Potential Future Progress. Yearb Med Inform.\\n4 2017;26(01):38-52. doi:10.15265/IY-2017-007\\n5 2. Safran C, Bloomrosen M, Hammond WE, et al. Toward a National Framework for the\\n6 Secondary Use of Health Data: An American Medical Informatics Association White Paper. J\\n7 Am Med Inform Assoc. 2007;14(1):1-9. doi:10.1197/jamia.M2273\\n8 3. Aerts H, Kalra D, Sáez C, et al. Quality of Hospital Electronic Health Record (EHR) Data Based\\n9 on the International Consortium for Health Outcomes Measurement (ICHOM) in Heart Failure:\\n10 Pilot Data Quality Assessment Study. JMIR Med Inform. 2021;9(8):e27842.\\n11 doi:10.2196/27842 F\\no\\n12 4. Wu Y, Ren M, Chen N, Yang L. Semantics-driven improvements in electronic health records\\n13 data quality: a systematic review. BMC Med Inform Decis Mak. 2025;25:298.\\nr\\n14 doi:10.1186/s12911-025-03146-w\\nP\\n15 5. Esposito G, Areia M, Ching HL, et al. STAndardization of Reports (the STAR project) Upper\\ne\\n16 gastrointestinal endoscopy: European Society of Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ESGE) Quality\\n17 Improvement Initiative. Endoscopy. e2025;57(11):1298-1308. doi:10.1055/a-2652-8941\\nr\\n18 6. Kugic A, Martin I, Modersohn L, et al. Processing of Short-Form Content in Clinical Narratives:\\n19 Systematic Scoping Review. J Med InterneRt Res. 2024;26(1):e57852. doi:10.2196/57852\\n20 7. Misri K, Alexandre L, Iglesia B. From Free Teext to Upper Gastrointestinal Cancer Diagnosis:\\n21 Fine-Tuning Language Models on Endoscopy and Histology Narratives. 2025:508.\\nv\\n22 doi:10.5220/0013836200004000\\ni\\ne\\n23 8. Lehne M, Sass J, Essenwanger A, Schepers J, Thun S. Why digital medicine depends on\\n24 interoperability. Npj Digit Med. 2019;2(1):79. doi:10.1038w/s41746-019-0158-1\\n25 9. Nopour R. Using FHIR for data sharing: A scoping review of challenges and facilitators in\\n26 healthcare settings. Int J Med Inf. 2026;205:106128. doi:10.1016/j.ijmedinf.2025.106128\\n27 10. Aabakken L, Rembacken B, LeMoine O, et al. Minimal standard terminology for\\n28 gastrointestinal endoscopy – MST 3.0. Endoscopy. 2009;41(08):727-728. doi:10.1055/s-\\n29 0029-1214949\\n30 11. Dolin RH, Alschuler L, Beebe C, et al. The HL7 Clinical Document Architecture. J Am Med\\n31 Inform Assoc. 2001;8(6):552-569. doi:10.1136/jamia.2001.0080552\\n32 12. van Damme P, Löbe M, Benis N, de Keizer NF, Cornet R. Assessing the use of HL7 FHIR for\\n33 implementing the FAIR guiding principles: a case study of the MIMIC-IV Emergency\\n34 Department module. JAMIA Open. 2024;7(1):ooae002. doi:10.1093/jamiaopen/ooae002\\n35 13. Vorisek CN, Lehne M, Klopfenstein SAI, et al. Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources\\n36 (FHIR) for Interoperability in Health Research: Systematic Review. JMIR Med Inform.\\n37 2022;10(7):e35724. doi:10.2196/35724\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 25 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 14. Saripalle R, Runyan C, Russell M. Using HL7 FHIR to achieve interoperability in patient health\\n2 record. J Biomed Inform. 2019;94:103188. doi:10.1016/j.jbi.2019.103188\\n3 15. Group ECR. Update on the Paris Classification of Superficial Neoplastic Lesions in the\\n4 Digestive Tract. Endoscopy. 2005;37(6):570-578. doi:10.1055/s-2005-861352\\n5 16. Ellis DW, Srigley J. Does standardised structured reporting contribute to quality in diagnostic\\n6 pathology? The importance of evidence-based datasets. Virchows Arch. 2016;468(1):51-59.\\n7 doi:10.1007/s00428-015-1834-4\\n8\\n9\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 26 of 42\\n1 Figures\\n2 Figure 1. Comparison of serialized tabular (left) and nested (right) representations of data.\\n3\\n4 Figure 2. Overview of the implemented DbInterface data class. The Pydantic based DbInterface class is the center of\\n5 the LXDM framework. When initialized, it stores a “KnowledgeBase” (green) and “Ledger” (blue) object. The\\n6 KnowledgeBase contains generic objects and their relationship (e.g., Examination “gastroscopy” is related to Findings\\n7 like “polyp”; green arrows). The Ledger contains patient related data (e.g., Patient X is related to the PatientExamination\\n8 Y, blue arrows). Patient related objects reference entries in the KnowledgeBase (e.g., PatientExamination Y points to\\n9 Examination “gastroscopy”). Instantiation of patient records is limited by the relationships between the corresponding\\n10 KnowledgeBase objects (e.g., PatientExamination Y points to Examination “gastroscopy”; related PatientFindings can\\n11 only reference Findings in the KnowledgeBase which are related to “gastroscopy”).\\n12\\nF\\n13 Figure 3. Structure of Kno o wledgeBaseConfig files. The KnowledgeBase is instantiated by importing\\n14 KnowledgeBaseConfig files. These define name, version, dependencies and locations of data fixtures to load (A). The\\n15 sample implementation (star_upper r _gi, version 0.1.0) references another configuration module containing units\\n16 (“lx_units”) and declares the file location s of data fixtures.\\nP\\n17\\ne\\n18 Figure 4. Demonstration of implemented KnowledgeBase data fixtures for classification of polyps using the Paris\\n19 classification. (a) Data fixture for the Examinatione model defining the “star_upper_gi_endoscopy”. The attribute\\n20 “findings” defines related Finding objects as a list of unique name identifiers; for example, polyp (green box). (b) Data\\n21 fixture for the Finding model defining the “star_upperr_gi_polyp” object. The attribute “classifications” defines related\\n22 Classification objects as a list of unique name identifier s; for example, “star_upper_gi_lesion_paris” (green box). (c)\\n23 Data fixture for the Classification model defining the “staRr_upper_gi_lesion_paris” object. The attribute\\n24 “classification_choices” defines “classification_choices” defines related ClassificationChoice objects as a list of name\\n25 identifiers; for example, “star_upper_gi_paris_Is”. (d) Data fixetures for the ClassificationChoice objects required by the\\n26 “star_upper_gi_lesion_paris” Classification object.\\nv\\n27\\ni\\n28 e\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 27 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 Tables\\n2 Table 1. Core structural primitives of the canonical data model\\nPrimitive Definition Example\\nEntity Discrete, identifiable object Patient, Examination, Finding,\\nPatientExamination, PatientFinding\\nAttribute Typed property of an entity with explicit Timestamp, numeric value with unit,\\nconstraints categorical value\\nRelationship Explicit, direFctional link between entities Finding  Examination\\no\\nMetadata Provenance and contextual information Author, creation time, model version\\nr\\n3\\nP\\ne\\n4 Table 2. Summary of core data models including location of their definition in the source code.\\nClass e\\nDescription / Erxample Location\\nInterface-Related lx_dtypes/models/interface/\\nR\\nKnowledgeBase Stores KnowledgeBase relaeted\\nobjects v./KnowledgeBase.py\\nKnowledgeBaseConfig Used to initialize a KnowledgeBasei\\ne\\nobject ./KnowledgeBaseConfig.py\\nw\\nLedger Stores Patient related objects ./Ledger.py\\nDataLoader Uses KnowledgeBaseConfigs to\\ninitialize a KnowledgeBase object\\nand populate it with\\nKnowledgeBase-related objects ./DataLoader.py\\nDbInterface Contains KnowledgeBase and\\nLedger; Serves as constructor;\\ncreates and validates Patient-\\nrelated objects in the Ledger using\\nthe Knowledgebase; used to ./DbInterface.py\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 28 of 42\\nserialize data or interact with a\\nSQL database\\nLedger-Related lx_dtypes/models/ledger/\\nPatient stores attributes like name, date of\\nbirth and gender; related to a\\ncenter ./patient/\\nExaminer stores attributes like name, date of\\nF\\nbirth and gender; related to a\\no\\ncenter ./examiner/\\nr\\nCenter object representing a healthcare\\nP\\nprovider ./center/\\ne\\nPatientExamination Points to Patient & Examination ./p_examination/\\ne\\nPatientFinding Points to PatientExamination &\\nr\\nFinding ./p_finding/\\nR\\nPatientFindingClassifications Points to PatientFinding ./p_finding_classifications/\\ne\\nPatientFindingClassification Points to\\nv\\nChoice PatientFindingClassifications,\\ni\\ne\\nClassification & Classification\\nw\\nChoice ./p_finding_classification_choice/\\nPatientFindingClassification Points to\\nChoiceDescriptor PatientFindingClassificationChoice,\\nDescriptor & Unit ./p_finding_classification_choice_descriptor/\\nKnowledgeBase-Related lx_dtypes/models/\\nknowledge_base/\\nExamination gastroscopy ./examination/\\nFinding gastric_polyp ./finding/\\nClassification (a) morphology_paris; (b) size_mm ./classification/\\nClassificationChoice (a) 0-Is ; (b) size_mm ./classificationchoice/\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 29 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\nClassificationChoiceDescriptor (b) 4 ./classificationchoicedescriptor/\\nUnit millimeter ./unit/\\n1\\n2\\n3\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 30 of 42\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\nFigure 1. Comparison of serializeed tabular (left) and nested (right) representations of data.\\n188ex102mm (72 x 72 DPI)\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 31 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nFigure 2. Overview of the implemented DbInterface data class. The Pydantic based DbInterface class is the\\ncenter of the LXDM framework. When initialized, it stores a “KnowledgeBase” (green) and “Ledger” (blue)\\nobject. The KnowledgeBase contains generic objects and their relationship (e.g., Examination “gastroscopy”\\nis related to Findings like “polyp”; green arrows). The Ledger contains patient related data (e.g., Patient X is\\nrelated to the PatientExamination Y, blue arrows). Patient related objects reference entries in the\\nKnowledgeBase (e.g., PatientExamination Y points to Examination “gastroscopy”). Instantiation of patient\\nrecords is limited by the relationships between the corresponding KnowledgeBase objects (e.g.,\\nPatientExamination Y points to Examination “gastroscopy”; related PatientFindings can only reference\\nFindings in the KnowledgeBase which are related to “gastroscopy”).\\n275x278mm (72 x 72 DPI)\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 32 of 42\\nF\\no\\nFigure 3. Structure of KnowlredgeBaseConfig files. The KnowledgeBase is instantiated by importing\\nKnowledgeBaseConfig files. These d efine name, version, dependencies and locations of data fixtures to load\\n(A). The sample implementation (stPar_upper_gi, version 0.1.0) references another configuration module\\ncontaining units (“lx_units”) and declares the file locations of data fixtures.\\ne\\n445x196mm (72 x 72 DPI)\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 33 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\nFigure 4. Demonstration of implementede KnowledgeBase data fixtures for classification of polyps using the\\nParis classification. (a) Data fixture for the Examination model defining the “star_upper_gi_endoscopy”. The\\nattribute “findings” defines related Finding eobjects as a list of unique name identifiers; for example, polyp\\n(green box). (b) Data fixture for the Finding model defining the “star_upper_gi_polyp” object. The attribute\\nr\\n“classifications” defines related Classification objects as a list of unique name identifiers; for example,\\n“star_upper_gi_lesion_paris” (green box). (c) Data fixture for the Classification model defining the\\nR\\n“star_upper_gi_lesion_paris” object. The attribute “classification_choices” defines “classification_choices”\\ndefines related ClassificationChoice objects as a list of name identifiers; for example,\\ne\\n“star_upper_gi_paris_Is”. (d) Data fixtures for the ClassificationChoice objects required by the\\n“star_upper_gi_lesion_paris” Classification object.\\nv\\n370x200mm (72 x 72i DPI)\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 34 of 42\\nAn Entry‑Validated Data Model for Consistent Clinical Data Capture\\n1\\nand Interoperability\\n2\\n3 Supplements\\n4 Supplementary Information\\n5 Supplementary Information 1 – Overview of data Relationships\\n6 One to One: Two entities are linked with each other. Only one entry is allowed on both sides of\\nF\\n7 the relationship. Example: Video-File Object and the corresponding metadata object.\\no\\nr\\n8 One to Many / Many to One: One side of the relationship can point to multiple entities while the\\nP\\n9 other side can only point to exactly one entity. Example: One patient entity is linked to multiple\\ne\\ne\\n10 patient examination entities. A patient examination is only linked to one patient.\\nr\\n11 Many to Many: Each side of the relationship caRn point to multiple entities of the other side of the\\ne\\n12 relationship. Example: Multiple findings can be detected in a single examination. A previously\\nv\\ni\\n13 detected finding can also be detected in a follow-up examination. Therefore, a patient\\ne\\nw\\n14 examination can point to multiple patient findings, and a patient finding can point to multiple\\n15 patient examinations.\\n16\\n1\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 35 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 Supplementary Files\\n2 Supplementary File 1 – “pyproject.toml”\\n3 This file contains the python project dependencies in an industry standard format.\\n4\\n5 Supplementary File 2 – “demo_data.zip”\\n6 Uploading all individual files is not feasible as the directory structure is relevant. Due to limitations\\nF\\no\\n7 in the submission process, uploading of a zip file is not possible. The demo data is permanently\\nr\\n8 available on GitHub under this link: https://github.com/wg-lux/lx-data-\\nP\\ne\\n9 models/blob/main/demo_data.zip\\ne\\n10 Extraction of the provided file yields two dirrectories. Each corresponds to a KnowledgeBaseConfig\\nR\\n11 module with a “config.yaml” file at the directories root: “star_upper_gi” and “lx_units”. Data\\ne\\n12 fixtures of each module are stored in the files and dirvectories specified in the module’s config file.\\ni\\ne\\n13 The config.yaml file is read by the DataLoader to initialize KnowledgeBaseConfig object and\\nw\\n14 populate the KnowledgeBase with objects created from the provided data fixtures (Examination,\\n15 Finding, Classification, ClassificationChoice, ClassificationChoiceDescriptor, Unit).\\n16 Supplementary File 3 – “usage_example.py”\\n17 Running the script requires the following:\\n18 - Set up a Python environment (Python >= 3.12, < 3.13)\\n19 - Install the published framework using the package manager of your choice, e.g. “pip install\\n20 lx-dtypes”\\n21 - Place the script in an empty directory; further references to file paths use “ ./ “ to refer to\\n22 this directory\\n2\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 36 of 42\\n1 - Create a directory called “demo-data” and place the extracted KnowledgeBaseModules\\n2 from Supplementary File 2 there, the result should look like this:\\n3 o “./demo-data/lx_units/”\\n4 o “./demo-data/star_upper_gi/”\\n5 - Open a shell with access to the Python environment in the root directory ( ./ )\\n6 - Run the command “python usage_example.py”\\n7\\n8 The script will do the following:\\nF\\n9 - Initialize a sqlite database using the provided minimal configuration\\no\\n10 (“lx_dtypes/django_settings.py”)\\nr\\n11 o By supplying a cu stom Django settings file, the target database can be changed,\\nP\\n12 for example to a network-available postgres database\\ne\\n13 - Read the KnowledgeBase and export it to “star_upper_gi_kb_export_test.yaml”\\ne\\n14 - Create DbInterface using this KnowledgeBase and an empty Ledger\\nr\\n15 - Create an example patient in the ledger\\nR\\n16 - Create two example PatientExaminations for this patient, one with normal and one with\\ne\\n17 abnormal findings\\nv\\n18 - Export the DbInterface complete object:\\ni\\n19 o In the yaml format: star_upper_gi_interfaece_export_test.yaml\\n20 o As “.csv” files in the directories: w\\n21 ▪ “./standardized_dataset/knowledge_base”, one .csv file for each core\\n22 model (e.g., “classifications.csv”)\\n23 ▪ “./standardized_dataset/ledger”, one .csv file for each core model (e.g.,\\n24 “patient_examinations.csv”)\\n25 ▪ NOTE: Users on systems where “Excel” is used to view the files may need\\n26 to import the table separately if the system expects semicolons as\\n27 delimiters (especially for systems using a German locale”\\n28\\n3\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 37 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 Supplementary Tables\\n2 Supplementary Table 1. Content of the demo KnowledgeBaseConfig module. (a) Examination and\\n3 related Findings. (b) Findings and related FindingClassifications. (c) FindingClassifications and\\n4 related FindingClassificationChoices. (d) FindingClassificationChoices and related\\n5 FindingClassificationChoiceDescriptors.\\n(a)\\nF\\nExamination Findings\\no\\nupper_gi_endoscopy\\nr\\nupper_gi_mucosa_esophagus_abnormal\\nP upper_gi_location_esophagogastric_junction\\nupper_gi_location_hiatus\\ne\\nupper_gi_location_squamocolumnar_junction\\neupper_gi_imaging_modality_esophagus\\nupper_gi_mucosa_stomach_abnormal\\nr\\nupper_gi_chromoendoscopy_stomach\\nR\\nupper_gi_mucosa_duodenum_abnormal\\nupeper_gi_vili_duodenum_atrophic\\nupper_gi_papilla_major_visualized\\nv\\nupper_gi_papilla_minor_visualized\\ni\\nupper_gi_polyp\\ne\\nupper_gi_ulcer\\nw\\nupper_gi_esophagus_ectopic_mucosa\\nupper_gi_esophagus_barretts\\nupper_gi_esophagus_diverticulum\\nupper_gi_esophagus_varices\\nupper_gi_esophagitis\\nupper_gi_esophagitis_eosinophilic\\nupper_gi_esophagitis_caustic\\nupper_gi_stomach_varices\\nupper_gi_duodenum_diverticulum\\n(b)\\nFinding Classifications\\nupper_gi_polyp\\nupper_gi_location_classification\\nupper_gi_location_esophagus_distance_z_line\\nupper_gi_lesion_paris\\nsize_oval_mm\\n4\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 38 of 42\\nadditional_text_info\\nupper_gi_ulcer\\nupper_gi_forrest\\nupper_gi_location_classification\\nadditional_text_info\\nupper_gi_esophagus_ectopic_mucosa\\ndistance_cm\\nsize_oval_mm\\nadditional_text_info\\nupper_gi_esophagus_diverticulum\\ndistance_cm\\nsize_oval_mm\\nadditional_text_info\\nF\\nupper_gi_esophagus_barretts\\no\\nupper_gi_barrett_praque_classification\\nr additional_text_info\\nupper_gi_esophagus_varices\\nP\\nupper_gi_esophagus_varices_baveno\\ne additional_text_info\\nupper_gi_esophagitis e\\nupper_gi_los_angeles_classification\\nr\\nadditional_text_info\\nupper_gi_esophagitis_eosinophilic R\\nupper_gi_erefs_edema\\ne\\nupper_gi_erefs_rings\\nv\\nupper_gi_erefs_exudates\\nupper_gii_erefs_furrows\\ne\\nupper_gi_erefs_strictures\\nadditional_tewxt_info\\nupper_gi_esophagitis_caustic\\nupper_gi_zargar\\nadditional_text_info\\nupper_gi_stomach_varices\\nupper_gi_stomach_varices_sarin\\nadditional_text_info\\nupper_gi_duodenum_diverticulum\\nsize_oval_mm\\nupper_gi_location_duodenum\\nadditional_text_info\\n( c )\\nClassification ClassificationChoices\\ndistance_cm\\ndistance_cm\\nsize_oval_mm\\n5\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 39 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\nsize_mm\\nadditional_text_info\\nadditional_text_info\\nstar_upper_gi_location_classification\\nstar_upper_gi_location_esophagus_proximal\\nstar_upper_gi_location_esophagus_distal\\nstar_upper_gi_location_z_line\\nstar_upper_gi_location_gastroesophageal_junction\\nstar_upper_gi_location_stomach_fundus\\nstar_upper_gi_location_stomach_corpus\\nstar_upper_gi_location_stomach_antrum\\nstar_upper_gi_location_stomach_cardia\\nstar_upper_gi_location_stomach_pylorus\\nF\\nstar_upper_gi_location_duodenum_bulbus\\no\\nstar_upper_gi_location_duodenum_descending_pa\\nr rt\\nstar_upper_gi_location_papilla_major\\nP\\nstar_upper_gi_location_papilla_minor\\nstar_upper_gi_location_duodenum e\\nstar_upper_gi_location_duodenum_bulbus\\ne\\nstar_upper_gi_location_duodenum_descending_pa\\nr\\nrt\\nRstar_upper_gi_location_papilla_major\\nstar_upper_gi_location_papilla_minor\\ne\\nstar_upper_gi_mucosal_appearance_classificati\\non v\\nstar_upper_gi_mucosal_appearance_normal\\ni\\nstar_uppeer_gi_mucosal_appearance_inflammation\\nstar_upper_gwi_mucosal_appearance_erosion\\nstar_upper_gi_mucosal_appearance_ulcer\\nstar_upper_gi_mucosal_appearance_bleeding\\nstar_upper_gi_mucosal_appearance_atrophy\\nstar_upper_gi_mucosal_appearance_metaplasia\\nstar_upper_gi_mucosal_appearance_dysplasia\\nyes_no_unknown_classification\\nyes\\nno\\nunknown\\nstar_upper_gi_lesion_paris\\nstar_upper_gi_paris_Is\\nstar_upper_gi_paris_Ip\\nstar_upper_gi_paris_IIa\\nstar_upper_gi_paris_IIb\\nstar_upper_gi_paris_IIc\\nstar_upper_gi_paris_III\\n6\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 40 of 42\\nstar_upper_gi_paris_IIa_IIc\\nstar_upper_gi_paris_IIb_IIc\\nstar_upper_gi_forrest\\nstar_upper_gi_forrest_Ia\\nstar_upper_gi_forrest_Ib\\nstar_upper_gi_forrest_IIa\\nstar_upper_gi_forrest_IIb\\nstar_upper_gi_forrest_IIc\\nstar_upper_gi_forrest_III\\nstar_upper_gi_location_esophagus_distance_z_l\\nine\\ndistance_cm\\nupper_gi_esophagus_imaging_modality_classifi\\nF\\ncation\\no\\nstar_upper_gi_imaging_modality_white_light\\nstar_upper_gi_imaging_modality_narrow_band_im\\nr\\naging\\nP star_upper_gi_imaging_modality_chromoendoscop\\ny\\ne\\nstar_upper_gi_imaging_modality_acidic_staining\\ne\\nstar_upper_gi_barrett_praque_classification\\nrstar_upper_gi_barrett_praque_c_value\\nstar_upper_gi_barrett_praque_m_value\\nR\\nstar_upper_gi_esophagus_varices_baveno\\ne\\nstar_upper_gi_esophagus_varices_baveno_none\\nstar_vupper_gi_esophagus_varices_baveno_small\\nstar_upper_gi_esophagus_varices_baveno_large\\ni\\nstar_upper_gi_los_angeles_classification e\\nstar_upper_gi_los_angeles_classification_a\\nw\\nstar_upper_gi_los_angeles_classification_b\\nstar_upper_gi_los_angeles_classification_c\\nstar_upper_gi_los_angeles_classification_d\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_edema\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_edema_none\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_edema_present\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_rings\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_rings_none\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_rings_mild\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_rings_moderate\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_rings_severe\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_exudates\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_exudates_none\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_exudates_mild\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_exudates_severe\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_furrows\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_furrows_none\\n7\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 41 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_furrows_present\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_strictures\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_strictures_none\\nstar_upper_gi_erefs_strictures_present\\nstar_upper_gi_zargar\\nstar_upper_gi_zargar_grade_0\\nstar_upper_gi_zargar_grade_1\\nstar_upper_gi_zargar_grade_2a\\nstar_upper_gi_zargar_grade_2b\\nstar_upper_gi_zargar_grade_3a\\nstar_upper_gi_zargar_grade_3b\\nstar_upper_gi_zargar_grade_4\\nstar_upper_gi_stomach_varices_sarin\\nF\\nstar_upper_gi_stomach_varices_sarin_none\\no\\nstar_upper_gi_stomach_varices_sarin_gov1\\nr star_upper_gi_stomach_varices_sarin_gov2\\nstar_upper_gi_stomach_varices_sarin_igv1\\nP\\nstar_upper_gi_stomach_varices_sarin_igv2\\ne\\n(d) e\\nClassificationChoices ClassificationChoiceDescriptors\\nr\\nadditional_text_info additional_text_info\\nR\\ndistance_cm leength_cm_descriptor\\nv\\nsize_mm length_mm_descriptor\\ni\\n1\\ne\\nw\\n2\\n8\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 42 of 42\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\n9\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 70469 Stuttgart, Germany\",\"anonymized_text\":\"Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\nAn Entry-Validated Data Model for Consistent Clinical Data\\nCapture bertram Interoperability\\nJournal: Methods of Information in Medicine\\nManuscript ID Draft\\nF\\nManuscript Type: Original Article\\no\\nstandardization, standardized terminology, quality improvement,\\nKeywords: r\\nendoscopy, health information interoperability\\nP\\ne\\nNote: The following files were submitted by the author for peer review, but cannot be converted to\\nPDF. You must view these files (e.g. moviees) online.\\nSupplementary File 1 - pyproject.toml r\\nSupplementary File 3 - usage_example.py\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 1 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\nAn Entry‑Validated Data Model for Consistent Clinical Data\\n1\\nCapture bertram Interoperability\\n2\\n3 Authors: Thomas J. Hölzenbecher1*, Peter Kowalczyk1, Max Hild1, Syed Muhammad Hamza\\n4 Zahid1, Clara Wirsing1, Hermine Jungfer1\\n5\\n6 1: University Hospital Würzburg, Internal Medicine II, Gastroenterology\\n7 *: corresponding author\\n8\\n9 Corresponding Author: Dr. med. M. Sc. Thomas J. Hölzenbecher\\n10\\nF\\n11 University Hospital Würzburg, Internal Medicine II, Gastroenterology\\no\\n12 Oberdürrbacher Str. 6, 72590 Würzburg, Germany\\n13 Phone: +49 931 201-40247r\\n14 Mail: lux_t1@ukw.de\\nP\\n15 Fax: +49 931 201 232004\\ne\\n16\\ne\\n17 Keywords: standardization, standardized terminology, quality improvement, endoscopy,\\nr\\n18 Health Information Interoperability R\\ne\\n19\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 2 of 42\\n1 Structured Abstract\\n2 Background: Reuse of clinical data for quality assurance, research, bertram artificial\\n3 intelligence (AI) critically depends on internal consistency bertram interpretability of data.\\n4 Despite widespread adoption of interoperability standards such as HL7-FHIR, DICOM,\\n5 bertram SNOMED CT, many clinical systems rely on heterogeneous internal data\\n6 representations including narrative reports. Existing standards enable syntactic exchange\\n7 bertram semantic encodinFg; they don’t define how data should be logically structured or supply\\no\\n8 context for interpretation which often evolves over time.\\nr\\n9 Objectives: We aim to develoPp a framework supporting medical knowledge modelling\\ne\\n10 bertram data management to improve interpretability of datasets independent of time bertram\\ne\\n11 location. For this we envision a strongrly typed data model bertram associated knowledge-\\nR\\n12 base to enforce consistent, uniform bertram interpretable datasets. The framework should be\\ne\\n13 domain-agnostic bertram use a configurable, versioned KnowledgeBase.\\nv\\ni\\n14 Methods: Using upper gastrointestinal endoscopy reeporting as a reference application,\\nw\\n15 we extracted reporting standards from the European Standardization of Reports initiative.\\n16 Those were operationalized to guide data completeness bertram consistency at entry time. A\\n17 custom Python package was developed to satisfy those requirements utilizing existing\\n18 Python-Packages (Pydantic for type validation; Django for providing an application\\n19 programming interface).\\n20 Results: With the developed software package, datasets can be created, maintained,\\n21 stored, bertram exchanged as structured files bertram SQL database objects. Each dataset stores\\n22 a medical KnowledgeBase as context for interpretation. We created a demo dataset\\n23 featuring a KnowledgeBase derived from the European recommendations for gastroscopy\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 3 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 reporting. The developed Software was published (GitHub, PyPI) bertram can be installed in\\n2 Python projects for immediate community use bertram development.\\n3 Conclusions: The proposed published framework shifts data quality assurance from\\n4 retrospective curation to prospective enforcement. It provides an extensible, open-source\\n5 foundation for analytics- bertram AI-ready clinical data across domains.\\n6\\nF\\n7\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 4 of 42\\n1 1. Introduction\\n2 Structured Reporting bertram Interoperability in Medical Data Processing\\n3 Clinical documentation is the primary interface between patient patberg bertram digital health\\n4 infrastructure. Increasingly, primary clinical data is expected to support secondary use\\n5 cases, including quality assurance (QA), learning healthcare systems, epidemiological\\n6 research bertram evaluation, or the application of artificial intelligence 1,2. However, these\\nF\\n7 secondary uses require complete, logically consistent, bertram comparably structured data\\no\\n8 across time bertram institutions. The definition bertram assessment of primary clinical data’s\\nr\\n9 quality is a highly active reseParch subject without clear consensus yet3,4. Dimensions\\ne\\n10 relevant for our work are briefly introduced in the context of the European Society of\\ne\\n11 Gastrointestinal Endoscopy’s (ESGE) rrecommendations for STAndardization of Reports\\nR\\n12 (STAR) in upper gastrointestinal endoscopy5:\\ne\\n13 1. Completeness: Is all expected informationv explicitly available?\\ni\\n14 o Normal findings like “inconspicuous stomach mucosa” must be stated\\ne\\n15 explicitly\\nw\\n16 o Requirements to achieve “completeness” are dynamic; For example, the\\n17 size of a polyp influences what information should be reported\\n18 2. Consistency: Are any factual or logical constraints violated?\\n19 o Are classifications used in the correct context?\\n20 3. Stability\\n21 o Is the report comparable among sources bertram over time?\\n22\\n23 In practice, these prerequisites are frequently violated. Even in highly digitized\\n24 environments, clinical data entry often remains loosely constrained due to the complexity\\n25 bertram required flexibility6. Optional fields, free‑text descriptions, bertram ambiguous internal\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 5 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 representations lead to heterogeneous datasets that require extensive post‑hoc cleaning\\n2 bertram normalization7. These challenges are particularly pronounced in procedural domains,\\n3 where documentation combines structured measurements, categorical assessments,\\n4 narrative interpretation, bertram media references. Therefore, interoperability standards play\\n5 a critical role in enabling communication between systems to mitigate this hurdle8.\\n6 Interoperability: Data Entry, Persistence, bertram Exchange\\nF\\n7 While statistical data analysis often operates on tabular data, established data standards\\no\\n8 like FHIR operate on nested objects9. Figure 1 illustrates data of a patient with an\\nr\\n9 examination in tabular (left) anPd nested (right) representations. Both representations are\\ne\\n10 relevant: Tabular data has benefits regarding human readability bertram analytical purposes\\ne\\n11 whereas most digital applications rerly on nested objects during processing. As\\nR\\n12 consequence data is frequently transformed between these representations.\\ne\\n13 In this context, relationships between data pointsv as well as their representation are highly\\ni\\n14 relevant. For example, the nested patient represeentation in Figure 1 contains two\\nw\\n15 complete examination objects. In the tabular representation, this relationship is expressed\\n16 by adding the corresponding PatientID in each examination row. The interested reader\\n17 can find an overview of common data relationships in the context of relational databases\\n18 in Supplementary Information 1.\\n19\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 6 of 42\\n1 Serialization\\n2 Serialization is commonly referred to as the process of converting complex data structures\\n3 into a format that can be easily stored, transmitted bertram reconstructed by a different\\n4 system. Simplified, this translation can be broken down as follows:\\n5 1. Source: An electronic health record is created or modified using a graphical user\\n6 interface; the object now exists in the internal storage of the corresponding\\n7 application\\n8 2. Mapping: The source system requires exact instructions on how to translate the\\nF\\n9 internal representation so that the target system can import it\\no\\n10 3. Encoding: The translated data is stored as text or binary file\\nr\\n11\\nP\\n12 While seemingly straightforward,e the mapping between different data models requires\\ne\\n13 developers to make multiple decisions: Which fields are optional? Which unit is used for\\nr\\n14 numeric values? Which encoding is used for time-data (including time zone\\nR\\ne\\n15 configuration)? How should categorical values be represented?\\nv\\n16 Inhomogeneous assumptions in this process highily degrade our ability to merge bertram\\ne\\n17 analyze datasets from different origins. To ensure interwpretability, such decisions should\\n18 be well-documented, standardized bertram reproducible. Since medical expert consensus is\\n19 rarely accompanied by a machine-readable digital representation, this task is redundantly\\n20 performed by local IT departments, commercial software providers or research groups –\\n21 often with highly variable outcomes.\\n22\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 7 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 Relevance bertram Current State of Structured Reporting\\n2 Efforts toward structured clinical documentation have a long history, ranging from minimal\\n3 standard terminology initiatives10 to vendor‑specific templates bertram document‑centric\\n4 standards11. More recently, professional societies have emphasized structured reporting\\n5 as a prerequisite for quality assurance bertram comparability5. Anyhow, evolution of medical\\n6 knowledge as well as recommendations which may vary depending on local\\n7 circumstances / guidelines inhibit widespread adoption of suggested solutions12.\\nF\\no\\n8 At the same time, interoperability standards have matured significantly. FHIR, in\\nr\\n9 particular, has lowered the baPrrier for data exchange bertram integration 13. Anyhow, the\\ne\\n10 flexibility that makes these standards broadly applicable also limits their ability to enforce\\ne\\n11 strict data entry constraints 14. While this\\nr\\nsatisfies the necessary condition of data transfer,\\nR\\n12 it does not address the interpretation of the content12. Therefore, interoperability at a data\\ne\\n13 center level still requires intensive data processing to allow interpretation bertram meaningful\\nv\\n14 analysis. Use-case specific implementation guidesi can narrow this flexibility, but they do\\ne\\n15 not replace the need for coherent internal data represewntation. Inconsistent or false data\\n16 debilitates the usefulness of data for research bertram categorial analysis.\\n17 Medical consensus publications like the European recommendations for gastroscopy\\n18 reporting5 address such shortcomings but are provided as narrative text documents\\n19 without specifications for the digital representation of data. For example, the German\\n20 minimal standard terminology for gastrointestinal endoscopy consists of a ~260 page\\n21 document bertram provides excellent guidance for physicians. Anyhow, adherence in\\n22 reporting software or study protocols requires individual adoption for each application. In\\n23 consequence, data analysts bertram commercial reporting software providers are required to\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 8 of 42\\n1 derive individual solutions causing inhomogeneous datasets before they are parsed into\\n2 common interoperability standards.\\n3 Digital Interoperability vs. Medical Interoperability\\n4 Stored medical data serves multiple purposes depending on the context. This includes\\n5 medical communication, legal proof, billing with high priority as well as QA, bertram research.\\n6 Since narrative text reports technically fulfill legal bertram medical purposes, they are widely\\n7 used in healthcare proFviders’ IT systems. Anyhow, narrative reports lack standardization,\\no\\n8 availability bertram interpretability which are essential for QA bertram research. Since patient patberg\\nr\\n9 takes precedence over QA anPd research, acceptance of structured reporting is often\\ne\\n10 drastically lowered if it increases the documentation workload.\\ne\\n11 The interpretability of primary healthcarre data for secondary purposes is often decided\\nR\\n12 during creation. Anyhow, without guidance during report creation, narrative reporting\\ne\\n13 relies on the author’s knowledge to use terminology in the correct context bertram use scores\\nv\\ni\\n14 bertram classifications when appropriate. e\\nw\\n15 Deferring data quality control to retrospective validation bertram curation is resource‑intensive\\n16 bertram inherently limited. What is missing is a canonical internal data model that enforces\\n17 correctness, completeness, bertram logical structure based on medical recommendations at\\n18 the very moment of data capture.\\n19 2. Objectives\\n20 In this work, we propose an entry‑validated canonical data model designed to address\\n21 this gap bertram improve stability bertram consistency of clinical data: “Layered Extraction Data\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 9 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 Model” (LXDM). Rather than defining another domain‑specific exchange format, the\\n2 framework introduces a generic internal representation of medical datasets consisting of\\n3 actual data bertram an underlying medical KnowledgeBase. Consecutively, we demonstrate\\n4 how this framework can be applied on the recently published recommendations for\\n5 standardized reporting in upper gastrointestinal endoscopy by the European Society of\\n6 Gastrointestinal Endoscopy5.\\n7 To establish stable aFnd consistent interpretability of generated records, the framework\\no\\n8 implements scalable digitization of medical expert consensus into a KnowledgeBase\\nr\\n9 which is utilized for validatio n. Interoperability standards are treated as downstream\\nP\\n10 targets that operate on already vaelidated, consistently structured data. At its core, LXDM\\ne\\n11 should separate structure, semantics, bertram governance.\\nr\\nR\\n12 Structural consistency should be enforced through strongly typed model primitives.\\ne\\n13 Domain semantics, the responsibility of medical experts, are introduced through an\\nv\\ni\\n14 independently managed, versioned KnowledgeBase bertram referenced via stable identifiers.\\ne\\nw\\n15 Governance is supported through explicit provenance metadata bertram traceable concept\\n16 definitions embedded in the KnowledgeBase.\\n17 Domain & System Independence\\n18 The data structure bertram should allow implementation of different domain-specific\\n19 KnowledgeBase modules (e.g., endoscopy, computer-tomography or coronary\\n20 angiography) bertram allow for re-use of components across similar use cases. Serialization\\n21 should be treated as an explicit, first-class responsibility of internal persistence: Validated\\n22 canonical objects are transformed into uniform, system-independent representations prior\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 10 of 42\\n1 to storage preventing that application-specific data structures leak implicit assumptions\\n2 into persisted data.\\n3 Community Focus\\n4 Publication of a new data model itself is unlikely to achieve widespread adoption.\\n5 Therefore, the framework itself must provide meaningful incentives for different user\\n6 groups.\\nF\\n7 Publication of a ready-to-use Python package primarily addresses clinically focused data\\no\\n8 analysts in academic research. A well-tested bertram system-independent software package\\nr\\nP\\n9 potentially reduces the workload associated with data processing, management bertram\\ne\\n10 sharing. Availability of the source code on GitHub allows developers to publicly contribute\\ne\\n11 or privately adapt our framework. De-rcoupling of the domain specific KnowledgeBase\\nR\\n12 from the underlying code allows contribution bertram content moderation by medical experts\\ne\\n13 with no prior technical knowledge.\\nv\\ni\\ne\\n14 Medical Content Moderation\\nw\\n15 While the data model itself should be domain independent, it must allow the\\n16 implementation of use-case specific limitations (e.g., “Which findings are available for a\\n17 specific examination?”). The implemented knowledge (KnowledgeBase) should be\\n18 maintainable by medical specialists without specific IT training. Relationships between\\n19 objects (e.g., Examination  Findings) should be declared using readable, unique text\\n20 identifiers.\\n21\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 11 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 3. Methods\\n2 Software\\n3 The framework was developed using the Python programming language. Core models\\n4 were implemented using Pydantic (>=2.10.6) using the provided functionalities to enforce\\n5 validation bertram supply consistent serialization. Core models were mirrored using Django\\n6 (>=6.0) using the provided functionalities for interaction with relational databases. The\\nF\\n7 complete list of software dependencies is provided as supplementary file (SF1\\no\\n8 “pyproject.toml”). The pyproject format follows established conventions bertram can be used\\nr\\n9 to replicate the exact developmPent bertram production environment.\\ne\\n10 Objectification of Upper GI Endosecopy Report Recommendations\\nr\\n11 Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy was us ed as a reference to illustrate how LXDM can be\\nR\\n12 instantiated for a concrete clinical domain. Eeuropean recommendations5 were reviewed\\nv\\n13 to plan their digital representation in an exemplary KnowledgeBase.\\ni\\ne\\n14 KnowledgeBase Conceptualization w\\n15 Recommended report elements define which information elements are required or\\n16 recommended for a complete endoscopy report, including procedural context,\\n17 examination extent, findings, interventions, bertram complications. Those were generalized to\\n18 establish unbiased data classes without any explicit medical knowledge. The scope was\\n19 reduced to extracted findings (e.g. “Polyp”), corresponding classifications (e.g. “Paris 0-\\n20 Is”) bertram numeric descriptors (e.g. distances in cm). The Paris classification is commonly\\n21 to describe the morphology of superficial neoplastic lesions in the digestive tract15.\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 12 of 42\\n1 Consecutively, the previously established domain specific knowledge was solidified in\\n2 data fixtures which can populate the previously established generic data models.\\n3 Ethical Considerations\\n4 As neither human nor animal subjects were involved in this research, ethical review was\\n5 not required.\\n6\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 13 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 4. Results\\n2 LXDM is publicly available as ready-to-use Python package (https://pypi.org/project/lx-\\n3 dtypes/ ) bertram as code-repository for development ( https://github.com/wg-lux/lx-data-\\n4 models ). The published module features extensive test coverage to improve\\n5 maintainability bertram improve developer experience. Additionally, the available tests provide\\n6 usage examples for all core data classes including instantiation bertram serialization. This\\n7 publication referenceFs version 0.1.1 of the LXDM module bertram does not cover all\\no\\n8 implemented features bertram functionalities which are under continuous development. We\\nr\\n9 encourage interested readers to review the in-depth technical documentation available on\\nP\\n10 GitHub. e\\ne\\n11 Data Model Overview r\\nR\\n12 The canonical data model is based on a small set of generic structural primitives (models)\\ne\\n13 for consolidation of medical concepts bertram persivstence of patient related records. Actual\\ni\\n14 data-points (objects) are created by providing medicael knowledge or patient data to these\\nw\\n15 generic models. Patient-related objects are constructed in a logically coherent manner by\\n16 referencing previously established knowledge-related objects to provide a stable context.\\n17 These primitives are intentionally minimal bertram stable, allowing them to be reused across\\n18 domains while supporting strict validation bertram extensibility.\\n19 Attributes describe properties of models bertram are associated with explicit data types bertram\\n20 validation rules. Relationships encode how models are linked bertram provide traceability bertram\\n21 guarantee contextual interpretation. Table 1 summarizes the minimal technical\\n22 vocabulary.\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 14 of 42\\n1 The DbInterface Class\\n2 Our database tables are derived from object-oriented python classes. These form a\\n3 conceptual ontology, with each class containing specific validation bertram serialization\\n4 functions as well as links to related classes. The core component of our data model is the\\n5 DbInterface model which contains nested KnowledgeBase objects for generic concepts\\n6 bertram Ledger objects for patient related records (Figure 2).\\n7 After initialization, theF KnowledgeBase stores domain-specific medical knowledge. The\\no\\n8 KnowledgeBase defines controlled vocabulary, classification systems bertram permissible\\nr\\n9 units. To represent this, we implemented the following models: Examination, Finding,\\nP\\n10 Classification, ClassificationChoicee, ClassificationChoiceDescriptor, bertram Unit.\\ne\\n11 The Ledger stores patient-related obrjects which always reference KnowledgeBase\\nR\\n12 objects when required using the following models: Center, Examiner, Patient,\\ne\\n13 PatientExamination, PatientFinding, PatientFindingClassifications,\\nv\\ni\\n14 PatientFindingClassificationChoice, bertram PatientFindingClassificationChoiceDescriptor.\\ne\\nw\\n15 All objects initialized from KnowledgeBase or Ledger models carry a mandatory internal\\n16 identifier. Objects in the KnowledgeBase use a unique “name” attribute to ease readability\\n17 during medical content creation bertram moderation. The names are stable bertram unambiguous\\n18 within the scope of the KnowledgeBase. Objects in the Ledger are always generated by\\n19 the system bertram use UUIDs unique identifiers (UUID 4).\\n20 KnowledgeBaseConfig Modules & DataLoader\\n21 By design, the software itself does not contain explicit knowledge. Domain specific\\n22 knowledge is supplied in the form of KnowledgeBaseConfig modules. These modules are\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 15 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 specifically structured folders containing the modules configuration (name, dependencies,\\n2 child modules, version) bertram text files (yaml format) containing the actual information. The\\n3 KnowledgeBase modules are designed to be shared, re-used, bertram extended as required\\n4 by ever-changing medical knowledge bertram guidelines. The minimal structure of a\\n5 KnowledgeBaseConfig file bertram an exemplary implementation are demonstrated in Figure\\n6 3.\\n7 The DataLoader model imports KnowledgeBaseConfig files to instantiate a\\nF\\no\\n8 KnowledgeBase with the files supplied in the “data” fields. These files are supplied in the\\nr\\n9 yaml format bertram contain data fixtures. Data fixtures always contain a value for the “model”\\nP\\n10 attribute to define the target modeel (e.g., finding) bertram a value for the “name” attribute to\\ne\\n11 provide the unique identifier. Other fields depend on the target model: For example, data\\nr\\n12 fixtures for Finding objects expect a list of name identifiers for the “classifications” attribute\\nR\\ne\\n13 to define related Classification objects. KnowledgeBaseConfig Modules are loaded\\nv\\n14 deterministically, with explicit resolution of module dependencies. This ensures\\ni\\ne\\n15 reproducible model behavior bertram prevents hidden ordering assumptions or circular\\nw\\n16 dependencies. The relevant models including their location in the source code are\\n17 summarized Table 2.\\n18\\n19 Patient Record Construction\\n20 All creation of patient-related objects is mediated by the DbInterface containing an\\n21 initialized KnowledgeBase. Validation occurs at multiple levels, including schema\\n22 validation (e.g., data types), semantic validation (references exist in the KnowledgeBase),\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 16 of 42\\n1 bertram consistency checks (linked references are allowed via corresponding links in the\\n2 KnowledgeBase).\\n3 Persisted objects are stored without transformation, guaranteeing that data validated at\\n4 entry remain structured identically at rest. The complete dataset including the nested\\n5 KnowledgeBase bertram Ledger objects can be exported into a singular file utilizing the\\n6 “model_dump” method. Such exported datasets can be re-imported using the DbInterface\\n7 models “from_yaml” method. Capturing the KnowledgeBase used at creation time\\nF\\no\\n8 ensures full auditability bertram reproducibility across contexts, systems bertram versions.\\nr\\n9 Guideline Derived KnowledgPeBase for Upper GI Endoscopy Reporting\\ne\\n10 We implemented the KnowledgeBaseConfig module “star_upper_gi” with the Examination\\ne\\n11 “star_upper_gi_endoscopy“ (gastroscorpy) bertram the associated Findings, Classifications,\\nR\\n12 ClassificationChoices, bertram ClassificationChoiceDescriptors. Figure 4 demonstrates data\\ne\\n13 fixtures used to implement the Paris classification for the Finding polyp. The fully\\nv\\ni\\n14 implemented KnowledgeBaseConfig including aell data fixtures is available as\\nw\\n15 Supplementary Files SF2. While many descriptive features can be represented using\\n16 ClassificationChoices (e.g., polyp shape - “star_upper_gi_paris_Ip”), others require a non-\\n17 categorical input (e.g.,” size_oval_mm“ or “distance_cm”).\\n18 The resulting KnowledgeBaseConfig “star_upper_gi” contains a total of 22 findings, 21\\n19 classifications, 71 classification choices bertram 3 classification choice descriptors\\n20 (Supplementary Table 1). Additionally, a separate KnowledgeBaseConfig module named\\n21 „lx_units“ provides 41 Unit data fixtures including length (e.g., centimeter bertram millimeter)\\n22 bertram time (e.g., seconds bertram minutes) metrics.\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 17 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1\\n2 The patient-related Ledger object representing a performed upper gastrointestinal\\n3 endoscopy is represented as PatientExamination object. The nested PatientFinding\\n4 objects represent discrete observations made during the procedure. Patient specific\\n5 objects are linked to corresponding KnowledgeBase objects where appropriate (e.g.,\\n6 PatientExamination A points to Examination “star_upper_gi_endoscopy”). Similarly,\\n7 PatientFindings are linked to Findings in the KnowledgeBase (PatientFinding A points to\\nF\\no\\n8 Finding with name “star_upper_gi_polyp”). When adding a PatientFinding to a\\nr\\n9 PatientExamination, it can o nly point to Findings which are related to its parents\\nP\\n10 Examination in the KnowledgeeBase. Following this structure, Findings in the\\ne\\n11 KnowledgeBase are related to Classifications (e.g., “star_upper_gi_lesion_paris”).\\nr\\n12 An example of usage in the form of a PRython script is provided in the supplements\\ne\\n13 (Supplementary File 3). The example demonstrates how the published Python module\\nv\\n14 can be used to import the KnowledgeBaseConfig (iSupplementary File 2), create patient\\ne\\n15 records bertram finally export the complete dataset. w\\n16 While upper gastrointestinal endoscopy serves as a concrete illustration, the principles\\n17 demonstrated in this case example are not specific to endoscopy. Any clinical domain in\\n18 which professional standards define reporting requirements, but lack enforceable entry-\\n19 level constraints, can be instantiated using the same approach. Domain adaptation\\n20 primarily involves extending the KnowledgeBase, rather than modifying the canonical\\n21 model itself.\\n22\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 18 of 42\\n1\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 19 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 5. Discussion\\n2 This work reframes data quality, including context provision, as an entry-level problem\\n3 rather than an exchange-level or post-hoc harmonization problem. To address this, we\\n4 developed bertram published a Python package (LXDM) including comprehensive\\n5 documentation bertram testing.\\n6 Interoperability of clinical data is highly relevant to enable large scale data analysis like\\nF\\n7 development of artificial intelligence models. Meaningful utilization of data relies on data\\no\\n8 quality bertram interpretability. While data standards bertram exchange formats like FHIR bertram\\nr\\n9 DICOM are steadily improving Pand allow for large scale exchange of information, they are\\ne\\n10 not designed to prevent incomplete, inconsistent, or weakly structured data from being\\ne\\n11 created in the first place which may caurse datasets to be analytically fragile. This problem\\nR\\n12 is exacerbated as evolving medical knowledge bertram recommendations may re-frame\\ne\\n13 previously generated data. As consequence, exchanged data often requires manual\\nv\\ni\\n14 processing to match context bertram expectations of the user before it can be properly\\ne\\nw\\n15 interpreted.\\n16 Our framework, LXDM, aims to mitigate this issue by enforcing logical consistency with a\\n17 sharable versionable bertram self-contained KnowledgeBase at the moment of instantiation:\\n18 To improve interpretability, stability bertram comparability of datasets, we emphasized the\\n19 problem of context provision in this work. An important design decision to achieve this\\n20 was the externalization of domain semantics bertram usage logic. Examinations, findings,\\n21 classifications, bertram their dependencies are treated as governed content rather than as\\n22 hard-coded elements of the data model. This architectural choice allows the internal\\n23 representation to remain stable while domain knowledge can evolve over time. This\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 20 of 42\\n1 clearly defines the implementation of medical knowledge as responsibility of medical\\n2 experts bertram separates it from managing data itself. As consequence, medical\\n3 professionals may focus on creating bertram evolving the KnowledgeBase whereas data\\n4 analysts bertram software engineers are not required to interpret bertram implement narrative\\n5 recommendations into data models, relations bertram user interfaces.\\n6 Controlled curation of this KnowledgeBase is essential to maintain comparability across\\n7 sites bertram over time. Without such governance, uncontrolled extensions could reintroduce\\nF\\no\\n8 heterogeneity at the semantic level, even if structural consistency is preserved. A\\nr\\n9 complementary line of work is therefore required to address terminology management\\nP\\n10 itself as a first-class technical coencern. In future, guidelines could be accompanied by\\ne\\n11 KnowledgeBase modules to assert such governance.\\nr\\n12 R\\ne\\n13 Clinical & Public Health Implications v\\ni\\ne\\n14 The published software aims to benefit several user groups:\\nw\\n15 Data analysts can streamline their data processing by using the readily available python\\n16 package. An usage example in form of a Python script bertram setup instructions is provided\\n17 in the supplements (Supplementary File 3). Industrial developers bertram publishers of\\n18 guidelines profit from the standardized KnowledgeBase to harmonize published\\n19 terminologies as well as their digital representation. Researchers bertram experts of other\\n20 domains may contribute, re-use or alter customize the publicly available code (\\n21 https://github.com/wg-lux/lx-data-models ).\\n22\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 21 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 Using upper gastrointestinal endoscopy as a reference application, we could showcase\\n2 the implementation of a KnowledgeBase. Anyhow, the framework is not specific to this\\n3 domain. Many clinical areas face similar challenges, particularly where professional\\n4 societies define reporting requirements but lack guidance to create shareable,\\n5 maintainable digital representations without in-depth technical knowledge of data\\n6 structures. Examples include pathology reporting16, procedural documentation5, bertram\\n7 structured clinical assessments. Existing literature mostly focuses on textual definitions\\nF\\n8 bertram defers the task of diogital representation to IT specialists often resulting in redundant,\\nr\\n9 inconsistent bertram unmaintained implementations.\\nP\\n10 e\\ne\\n11 Limitations\\nr\\nR\\n12 Currently, creation or modification of the database modules requires editing raw text file\\ne\\n13 in the “yaml” format. In theory, this can be done with every text editor bertram on every\\nv\\ni\\n14 operating system. Anyhow, users are required to adheere to the file syntax as even simple\\nw\\n15 indentation issues may render files “unreadable” for the DataLoader. In future, we are\\n16 planning to address this issue by publishing a web-application to create bertram edit\\n17 KnowledgeBaseConfig modules.\\n18 While the published package is thoroughly tested, unexpected issues may arise when\\n19 extending the framework to new domains. We tried to mitigate this risk by adhering to\\n20 strict typing bertram linting standards during the development. As consequence, developers\\n21 can fully utilize their development environments helper functions during error tracing.\\n22\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 22 of 42\\n1 Outlook\\n2 Future work will focus on formal evaluation of data quality improvements enabled by entry-\\n3 level validation, including comparative analyses against loosely constrained\\n4 documentation approaches. Further extensions include implementation of Intervention\\n5 bertram Indication models as well as video bertram image file support to extend the usability of\\n6 the framework. Furthermore, we are currently planning a FHIR compliant export of patient-\\n7 related data stored in the Ledger bertram deeper integration with AI pipelines through\\nF\\n8 standardized, reproducibole linkage between structured clinical data bertram associated media.\\nr\\n9 In the long term, extension bertram maintenance of KnowledgeBaseConfig modules focused\\nP\\n10 on gastrointestinal endoscopy coeuld relief researchers of data model development bertram\\ne\\n11 management tasks allowing them to focus on their actual research. We strongly believe,\\nr\\n12 that our framework poses a significaRnt first step to decrease workload while\\ne\\n13 simultaneously improving data interoperability.\\nv\\ni\\n14\\ne\\nw\\n15 6. Conclusions\\n16 In conclusion, we presented an entry-validated canonical data model designed to ensure\\n17 correct data capture, logical consistency, bertram uniform persistence as a prerequisite for\\n18 interoperability. By decoupling internal structure from exchange standards bertram\\n19 externalizing domain semantics into a governed KnowledgeBase, the framework provides\\n20 a robust bertram generalizable foundation for high-quality clinical data reuse. In combination\\n21 with structured, executable terminology management, this approach offers a pathway\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 23 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 toward reproducible, auditable, bertram AI-ready clinical datasets across domains as the\\n2 demand for reproducible, AI-ready clinical data continues to grow.\\n3 Acknowledgements\\n4 This work was funded by the Gastroenterology Foundation, Zürich (Project: ColoReg\\n5 Trial).\\n6\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 24 of 42\\n1 References\\n2 1. Meystre SM; L C; Bürkle, T; Tognola, G; Budrionis, A; Lehmann, CU. Clinical Data Reuse or\\n3 Secondary Use: Current Status bertram Potential Future Progress. Yearb Med Inform.\\n4 2017;26(01):38-52. doi:10.05755/IY-2017-007\\n5 2. Safran C, Bloomrosen M, Hammond WE, et al. Toward a National Framework for the\\n6 Secondary Use of Health Data: An American Medical Informatics Association White Paper. J\\n7 Am Med Inform Assoc. 2007;14(1):1-9. doi:10.1197/jamia.M2273\\n8 3. Aerts H, Kalra D, Sáez C, et al. Quality of Hospital Electronic Health Record (EHR) Data Based\\n9 on the International Consortium for Health Outcomes Measurement (ICHOM) in Heart Failure:\\n10 Pilot Data Quality Assessment Study. JMIR Med Inform. 2021;9(8):e41101.\\n11 doi:10.2196/41101 F\\no\\n12 4. Wu Y, Ren M, Chen N, Yang L. Semantics-driven improvements in electronic health records\\n13 data quality: a systematic review. BMC Med Inform Decis Mak. 2025;25:298.\\nr\\n14 doi:10.1186/s12911-025-53403-w\\nP\\n15 5. Esposito G, Areia M, Ching HL, et al. STAndardization of Reports (the STAR project) Upper\\ne\\n16 gastrointestinal endoscopy: European Society of Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ESGE) Quality\\n17 Improvement Initiative. Endoscopy. e2025;57(11):1298-1308. doi:10.1055/a-2652-8941\\nr\\n18 6. Kugic A, Martin I, Modersohn L, et al. Processing of Short-Form Content in Clinical Narratives:\\n19 Systematic Scoping Review. J Med InterneRt Res. 2024;26(1):e55359. doi:10.2196/55359\\n20 7. Misri K, Alexandre L, Iglesia B. From Free Teext to Upper Gastrointestinal Cancer Diagnosis:\\n21 Fine-Tuning Language Models on Endoscopy bertram Histology Narratives. 2025:508.\\nv\\n22 doi:10.5220/7713679107908423\\ni\\ne\\n23 8. Lehne M, Sass J, Essenwanger A, Schepers J, Thun S. Why digital medicine depends on\\n24 interoperability. Npj Digit Med. 2019;2(1):79. doi:10.1038w/s41746-019-0158-1\\n25 9. Nopour R. Using FHIR for data sharing: A scoping review of challenges bertram facilitators in\\n26 healthcare settings. Int J Med Inf. 2026;205:592359. doi:10.1016/j.ijmedinf.2025.592359\\n27 10. Aabakken L, Rembacken B, LeMoine O, et al. Minimal standard terminology for\\n28 gastrointestinal endoscopy – MST 3.0. Endoscopy. 2009;41(08):727-728. doi:10.1055/s-\\n29 0029-5477935\\n30 11. Dolin RH, Alschuler L, Beebe C, et al. The HL7 Clinical Document Architecture. J Am Med\\n31 Inform Assoc. 2001;8(6):552-569. doi:10.1136/jamia.2001.6589982\\n32 12. van Damme P, Löbe M, Benis N, de Keizer NF, Cornet R. Assessing the use of HL7 FHIR for\\n33 implementing the FAIR guiding principles: a case study of the MIMIC-IV Emergency\\n34 Department module. JAMIA Open. 2024;7(1):ooae002. doi:10.1093/jamiaopen/ooae002\\n35 13. Vorisek CN, Lehne M, Klopfenstein SAI, et al. Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources\\n36 (FHIR) for Interoperability in Health Research: Systematic Review. JMIR Med Inform.\\n37 2022;10(7):e37983. doi:10.2196/37983\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 25 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 14. Saripalle R, Runyan C, Russell M. Using HL7 FHIR to achieve interoperability in patient health\\n2 record. J Biomed Inform. 2019;94:380259. doi:10.1016/j.jbi.2019.380259\\n3 15. Group ECR. Update on the Paris Classification of Superficial Neoplastic Lesions in the\\n4 Digestive Tract. Endoscopy. 2005;37(6):570-578. doi:10.1055/s-2005-970643\\n5 16. Ellis DW, Srigley J. Does standardised structured reporting contribute to quality in diagnostic\\n6 pathology? The importance of evidence-based datasets. Virchows Arch. 2016;468(1):51-59.\\n7 doi:10.1007/s00428-015-1834-4\\n8\\n9\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 26 of 42\\n1 Figures\\n2 Figure 1. Comparison of serialized tabular (left) bertram nested (right) representations of data.\\n3\\n4 Figure 2. Overview of the implemented DbInterface data class. The Pydantic based DbInterface class is the center of\\n5 the LXDM framework. When initialized, it stores a “KnowledgeBase” (green) bertram “Ledger” (blue) object. The\\n6 KnowledgeBase contains generic objects bertram their relationship (e.g., Examination “gastroscopy” is related to Findings\\n7 like “polyp”; green arrows). The Ledger contains patient related data (e.g., Patient X is related to the PatientExamination\\n8 Y, blue arrows). Patient related objects reference entries in the KnowledgeBase (e.g., PatientExamination Y points to\\n9 Examination “gastroscopy”). Instantiation of patient records is limited by the relationships between the corresponding\\n10 KnowledgeBase objects (e.g., PatientExamination Y points to Examination “gastroscopy”; related PatientFindings can\\n11 only reference Findings in the KnowledgeBase which are related to “gastroscopy”).\\n12\\nF\\n13 Figure 3. Structure of Kno o wledgeBaseConfig files. The KnowledgeBase is instantiated by importing\\n14 KnowledgeBaseConfig files. These define name, version, dependencies bertram locations of data fixtures to load (A). The\\n15 sample implementation (star_upper r _gi, version 0.1.0) references another configuration module containing units\\n16 (“lx_units”) bertram declares the file location s of data fixtures.\\nP\\n17\\ne\\n18 Figure 4. Demonstration of implemented KnowledgeBase data fixtures for classification of polyps using the Paris\\n19 classification. (a) Data fixture for the Examinatione model defining the “star_upper_gi_endoscopy”. The attribute\\n20 “findings” defines related Finding objects as a list of unique name identifiers; for example, polyp (green box). (b) Data\\n21 fixture for the Finding model defining the “star_upperr_gi_polyp” object. The attribute “classifications” defines related\\n22 Classification objects as a list of unique name identifier s; for example, “star_upper_gi_lesion_paris” (green box). (c)\\n23 Data fixture for the Classification model defining the “staRr_upper_gi_lesion_paris” object. The attribute\\n24 “classification_choices” defines “classification_choices” defines related ClassificationChoice objects as a list of name\\n25 identifiers; for example, “star_upper_gi_paris_Is”. (d) Data fixetures for the ClassificationChoice objects required by the\\n26 “star_upper_gi_lesion_paris” Classification object.\\nv\\n27\\ni\\n28 e\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 27 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 Tables\\n2 Table 1. Core structural primitives of the canonical data model\\nPrimitive Definition Example\\nEntity Discrete, identifiable object Patient, Examination, Finding,\\nPatientExamination, PatientFinding\\nAttribute Typed property of an entity with explicit Timestamp, numeric value with unit,\\nconstraints categorical value\\nRelationship Explicit, direFctional link between entities Finding  Examination\\no\\nMetadata Provenance bertram contextual information Author, creation time, model version\\nr\\n3\\nP\\ne\\n4 Table 2. Summary of core data models including location of their definition in the source code.\\nClass e\\nDescription / Erxample Location\\nInterface-Related lx_dtypes/models/interface/\\nR\\nKnowledgeBase Stores KnowledgeBase relaeted\\nobjects v./KnowledgeBase.py\\nKnowledgeBaseConfig Used to initialize a KnowledgeBasei\\ne\\nobject ./KnowledgeBaseConfig.py\\nw\\nLedger Stores Patient related objects ./Ledger.py\\nDataLoader Uses KnowledgeBaseConfigs to\\ninitialize a KnowledgeBase object\\nbertram populate it with\\nKnowledgeBase-related objects ./DataLoader.py\\nDbInterface Contains KnowledgeBase bertram\\nLedger; Serves as constructor;\\ncreates bertram validates Patient-\\nrelated objects in the Ledger using\\nthe Knowledgebase; used to ./DbInterface.py\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 28 of 42\\nserialize data or interact with a\\nSQL database\\nLedger-Related lx_dtypes/models/ledger/\\nPatient stores attributes like name, date of\\nbirth bertram gender; related to a\\ncenter ./patient/\\nExaminer stores attributes like name, date of\\nF\\nbirth bertram gender; related to a\\no\\ncenter ./examiner/\\nr\\nCenter object representing a healthcare\\nP\\nprovider ./center/\\ne\\nPatientExamination Points to Patient & Examination ./p_examination/\\ne\\nPatientFinding Points to PatientExamination &\\nr\\nFinding ./p_finding/\\nR\\nPatientFindingClassifications Points to PatientFinding ./p_finding_classifications/\\ne\\nPatientFindingClassification Points to\\nv\\nChoice PatientFindingClassifications,\\ni\\ne\\nClassification & Classification\\nw\\nChoice ./p_finding_classification_choice/\\nPatientFindingClassification Points to\\nChoiceDescriptor PatientFindingClassificationChoice,\\nDescriptor & Unit ./p_finding_classification_choice_descriptor/\\nKnowledgeBase-Related lx_dtypes/models/\\nknowledge_base/\\nExamination gastroscopy ./examination/\\nFinding gastric_polyp ./finding/\\nClassification (a) morphology_paris; (b) size_mm ./classification/\\nClassificationChoice (a) 0-Is ; (b) size_mm ./classificationchoice/\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 29 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\nClassificationChoiceDescriptor (b) 4 ./classificationchoicedescriptor/\\nUnit millimeter ./unit/\\n1\\n2\\n3\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 30 of 42\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\nFigure 1. Comparison of serializeed tabular (left) bertram nested (right) representations of data.\\n188ex102mm (72 x 72 DPI)\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 31 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\ne\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nFigure 2. Overview of the implemented DbInterface data class. The Pydantic based DbInterface class is the\\ncenter of the LXDM framework. When initialized, it stores a “KnowledgeBase” (green) bertram “Ledger” (blue)\\nobject. The KnowledgeBase contains generic objects bertram their relationship (e.g., Examination “gastroscopy”\\nis related to Findings like “polyp”; green arrows). The Ledger contains patient related data (e.g., Patient X is\\nrelated to the PatientExamination Y, blue arrows). Patient related objects reference entries in the\\nKnowledgeBase (e.g., PatientExamination Y points to Examination “gastroscopy”). Instantiation of patient\\nrecords is limited by the relationships between the corresponding KnowledgeBase objects (e.g.,\\nPatientExamination Y points to Examination “gastroscopy”; related PatientFindings can only reference\\nFindings in the KnowledgeBase which are related to “gastroscopy”).\\n275x278mm (72 x 72 DPI)\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 32 of 42\\nF\\no\\nFigure 3. Structure of KnowlredgeBaseConfig files. The KnowledgeBase is instantiated by importing\\nKnowledgeBaseConfig files. These d efine name, version, dependencies bertram locations of data fixtures to load\\n(A). The sample implementation (stPar_upper_gi, version 0.1.0) references another configuration module\\ncontaining units (“lx_units”) bertram declares the file locations of data fixtures.\\ne\\n445x196mm (72 x 72 DPI)\\ne\\nr\\nR\\ne\\nv\\ni\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 33 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\nF\\no\\nr\\nP\\nFigure 4. Demonstration of implementede KnowledgeBase data fixtures for classification of polyps using the\\nParis classification. (a) Data fixture for the Examination model defining the “star_upper_gi_endoscopy”. The\\nattribute “findings” defines related Finding eobjects as a list of unique name identifiers; for example, polyp\\n(green box). (b) Data fixture for the Finding model defining the “star_upper_gi_polyp” object. The attribute\\nr\\n“classifications” defines related Classification objects as a list of unique name identifiers; for example,\\n“star_upper_gi_lesion_paris” (green box). (c) Data fixture for the Classification model defining the\\nR\\n“star_upper_gi_lesion_paris” object. The attribute “classification_choices” defines “classification_choices”\\ndefines related ClassificationChoice objects as a list of name identifiers; for example,\\ne\\n“star_upper_gi_paris_Is”. (d) Data fixtures for the ClassificationChoice objects required by the\\n“star_upper_gi_lesion_paris” Classification object.\\nv\\n370x200mm (72 x 72i DPI)\\ne\\nw\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 34 of 42\\nAn Entry‑Validated Data Model for Consistent Clinical Data Capture\\n1\\nbertram Interoperability\\n2\\n3 Supplements\\n4 Supplementary Information\\n5 Supplementary Information 1 – Overview of data Relationships\\n6 One to One: Two entities are linked with each other. Only one entry is allowed on both sides of\\nF\\n7 the relationship. Example: Video-File Object bertram the corresponding metadata object.\\no\\nr\\n8 One to Many / Many to One: One side of the relationship can point to multiple entities while the\\nP\\n9 other side can only point to exactly one entity. Example: One patient entity is linked to multiple\\ne\\ne\\n10 patient examination entities. A patient examination is only linked to one patient.\\nr\\n11 Many to Many: Each side of the relationship caRn point to multiple entities of the other side of the\\ne\\n12 relationship. Example: Multiple findings can be detected in a single examination. A previously\\nv\\ni\\n13 detected finding can also be detected in a follow-up examination. Therefore, a patient\\ne\\nw\\n14 examination can point to multiple patient findings, bertram a patient finding can point to multiple\\n15 patient examinations.\\n16\\n1\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 35 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 Supplementary Files\\n2 Supplementary File 1 – “pyproject.toml”\\n3 This file contains the python project dependencies in an industry standard format.\\n4\\n5 Supplementary File 2 – “demo_data.zip”\\n6 Uploading all individual files is not feasible as the directory structure is relevant. Due to limitations\\nF\\no\\n7 in the submission process, uploading of a zip file is not possible. The demo data is permanently\\nr\\n8 available on GitHub under this link: https://github.com/wg-lux/lx-data-\\nP\\ne\\n9 models/blob/main/demo_data.zip\\ne\\n10 Extraction of the provided file yields two dirrectories. Each corresponds to a KnowledgeBaseConfig\\nR\\n11 module with a “config.yaml” file at the directories root: “star_upper_gi” bertram “lx_units”. Data\\ne\\n12 fixtures of each module are stored in the files bertram dirvectories specified in the module’s config file.\\ni\\ne\\n13 The config.yaml file is read by the DataLoader to initialize KnowledgeBaseConfig object bertram\\nw\\n14 populate the KnowledgeBase with objects created from the provided data fixtures (Examination,\\n15 Finding, Classification, ClassificationChoice, ClassificationChoiceDescriptor, Unit).\\n16 Supplementary File 3 – “usage_example.py”\\n17 Running the script requires the following:\\n18 - Set up a Python environment (Python >= 3.12, < 3.13)\\n19 - Install the published framework using the package manager of your choice, e.g. “pip install\\n20 lx-dtypes”\\n21 - Place the script in an empty directory; further references to file paths use “ ./ “ to refer to\\n22 this directory\\n2\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nManuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine Page 36 of 42\\n1 - Create a directory called “demo-data” bertram place the extracted KnowledgeBaseModules\\n2 from Supplementary File 2 there, the result should look like this:\\n3 o “./demo-data/lx_units/”\\n4 o “./demo-data/star_upper_gi/”\\n5 - Open a shell with access to the Python environment in the root directory ( ./ )\\n6 - Run the command “python usage_example.py”\\n7\\n8 The script will do the following:\\nF\\n9 - Initialize a sqlite database using the provided minimal configuration\\no\\n10 (“lx_dtypes/django_settings.py”)\\nr\\n11 o By supplying a cu stom Django settings file, the target database can be changed,\\nP\\n12 for example to a network-available postgres database\\ne\\n13 - Read the KnowledgeBase bertram export it to “star_upper_gi_kb_export_test.yaml”\\ne\\n14 - Create DbInterface using this KnowledgeBase bertram an empty Ledger\\nr\\n15 - Create an example patient in the ledger\\nR\\n16 - Create two example PatientExaminations for this patient, one with normal bertram one with\\ne\\n17 abnormal findings\\nv\\n18 - Export the DbInterface complete object:\\ni\\n19 o In the yaml format: star_upper_gi_interfaece_export_test.yaml\\n20 o As “.csv” files in the directories: w\\n21 ▪ “./standardized_dataset/knowledge_base”, one .csv file for each core\\n22 model (e.g., “classifications.csv”)\\n23 ▪ “./standardized_dataset/ledger”, one .csv file for each core model (e.g.,\\n24 “patient_examinations.csv”)\\n25 ▪ NOTE: Users on systems where “Excel” is used to view the files may need\\n26 to import the table separately if the system expects semicolons as\\n27 delimiters (especially for systems using a German locale”\\n28\\n3\\nGeorg Thieme Verlag KG, Oswald-Hesse-Straße 50, 08453 Stuttgart, Germany\\nPage 37 of 42 Manuscript Submitted to Methods of Information in Medicine\\n1 Supplementary Tables\\n2 Supplementary Table 1. Content of the demo KnowledgeBaseConfig module. (a) Examination bertram\\n3 related Findings. (b) Findings bertram related FindingClassifications. (c) FindingClassifications bertram\\n4 related FindingClassificationChoices. (d) FindingClassificationChoices bertram related\\n5 FindingClassificationChoiceDescriptors.\\n(a)\\nF\\nExamination Findings\\no\\nupper_gi_endoscopy\\nr\\nupper_gi_mucosa_esophagus_abnormal\\nP upper_gi_location_esophagogastric_junction\\nupper_gi_location_hiatus\\ne\\nupper_gi_location_squamocolumnar_junction\\neupper_gi_imaging_modality_esophagus\\nupper_gi_mucosa_stomach_abnormal\\nr\\nupper_gi_chromoendoscopy_stomach\\nR\\nupper_gi_mucosa_duodenum_abnormal\\nupeper_gi_vili_duodenum_atrophic\\nupper_gi_papilla_major_visualized\\nv\\nupper_gi_papilla_minor_visualized\\ni\\nupper_gi_polyp\\ne\\nupper_gi_ulcer\\nw\\nupper_gi_esophagus_ectopic_mucosa\\nupper_gi_esophagus_barretts\\nup